# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: rust
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:rust/ch03-01-variables-and-mutability] As mentioned in the “Storing Values with Variables” section, by default, variables are immutable.
[src:rust/ch03-01-variables-and-mutability] This is one of many nudges Rust gives you to write your code in a way that takes advantage of the safety and easy concurrency that Rust offers.
[src:rust/ch03-01-variables-and-mutability] However, you still have the option to make your variables mutable.
[src:rust/ch03-01-variables-and-mutability] Let’s explore how and why Rust encourages you to favor immutability and why sometimes you might want to opt out.
[src:rust/ch03-01-variables-and-mutability] When a variable is immutable, once a value is bound to a name, you can’t change that value.
[src:rust/ch03-01-variables-and-mutability] To illustrate this, generate a new project called *variables* in your *projects* directory by using `cargo new variables`.
[src:rust/ch03-01-variables-and-mutability] Save and run the program using `cargo run`.
[src:rust/ch03-01-variables-and-mutability] This example shows how the compiler helps you find errors in your programs.
[src:rust/ch03-01-variables-and-mutability] Compiler errors can be frustrating, but really they only mean your program isn’t safely doing what you want it to do yet; they do *not* mean that you’re not a good programmer!
[src:rust/ch03-01-variables-and-mutability] Experienced Rustaceans still get compiler errors.
[src:rust/ch03-01-variables-and-mutability] You received the error message cannot assign twice to immutable variable `x` because you tried to assign a second value to the immutable `x` variable.
[src:rust/ch03-01-variables-and-mutability] It’s important that we get compile-time errors when we attempt to change a value that’s designated as immutable, because this very situation can lead to bugs.
[src:rust/ch03-01-variables-and-mutability] If one part of our code operates on the assumption that a value will never change and another part of our code changes that value, it’s possible that the first part of the code won’t do what it was designed to do.
[src:rust/ch03-01-variables-and-mutability] The cause of this kind of bug can be difficult to track down after the fact, especially when the second piece of code changes the value only *sometimes*.
[src:rust/ch03-01-variables-and-mutability] The Rust compiler guarantees that when you state that a value won’t change, it really won’t change, so you don’t have to keep track of it yourself.
[src:rust/ch03-01-variables-and-mutability] Your code is thus easier to reason through.
[src:rust/ch03-01-variables-and-mutability] But mutability can be very useful and can make code more convenient to write.
[src:rust/ch03-01-variables-and-mutability] Although variables are immutable by default, you can make them mutable by adding `mut` in front of the variable name as you did in Chapter 2.
[src:rust/ch03-01-variables-and-mutability] Adding `mut` also conveys intent to future readers of the code by indicating that other parts of the code will be changing this variable’s value.
[src:rust/ch03-01-variables-and-mutability] We’re allowed to change the value bound to `x` from `5` to `6` when `mut` is used.
[src:rust/ch03-01-variables-and-mutability] Ultimately, deciding whether to use mutability or not is up to you and depends on what you think is clearest in that particular situation.
[src:rust/ch03-01-variables-and-mutability] Like immutable variables, *constants* are values that are bound to a name and are not allowed to change, but there are a few differences between constants and variables.
[src:rust/ch03-01-variables-and-mutability] First, you aren’t allowed to use `mut` with constants.
[src:rust/ch03-01-variables-and-mutability] Constants aren’t just immutable by default—they’re always immutable.
[src:rust/ch03-01-variables-and-mutability] You declare constants using the `const` keyword instead of the `let` keyword, and the type of the value *must* be annotated.
[src:rust/ch03-01-variables-and-mutability] We’ll cover types and type annotations in the next section, “Data Types”, so don’t worry about the details right now.
[src:rust/ch03-01-variables-and-mutability] Just know that you must always annotate the type.
[src:rust/ch03-01-variables-and-mutability] Constants can be declared in any scope, including the global scope, which makes them useful for values that many parts of code need to know about.
[src:rust/ch03-01-variables-and-mutability] The last difference is that constants may be set only to a constant expression, not the result of a value that could only be computed at runtime.
[src:rust/ch03-01-variables-and-mutability] The constant’s name is `THREE_HOURS_IN_SECONDS`, and its value is set to the result of multiplying 60 (the number of seconds in a minute) by 60 (the number of minutes in an hour) by 3 (the number of hours we want to count in this program).
[src:rust/ch03-01-variables-and-mutability] Rust’s naming convention for constants is to use all uppercase with underscores between words.
[src:rust/ch03-01-variables-and-mutability] The compiler is able to evaluate a limited set of operations at compile time, which lets us choose to write out this value in a way that’s easier to understand and verify, rather than setting this constant to the value 10,800.
[src:rust/ch03-01-variables-and-mutability] See the Rust Reference’s section on constant evaluation for more information on what operations can be used when declaring constants.
[src:rust/ch03-01-variables-and-mutability] Constants are valid for the entire time a program runs, within the scope in which they were declared.
[src:rust/ch03-01-variables-and-mutability] This property makes constants useful for values in your application domain that multiple parts of the program might need to know about, such as the maximum number of points any player of a game is allowed to earn, or the speed of light.
[src:rust/ch03-01-variables-and-mutability] Naming hardcoded values used throughout your program as constants is useful in conveying the meaning of that value to future maintainers of the code.
[src:rust/ch03-01-variables-and-mutability] It also helps to have only one place in your code that you would need to change if the hardcoded value needed to be updated in the future.
[src:rust/ch03-01-variables-and-mutability] As you saw in the guessing game tutorial in Chapter 2, you can declare a new variable with the same name as a previous variable.
[src:rust/ch03-01-variables-and-mutability] Rustaceans say that the first variable is *shadowed* by the second, which means that the second variable is what the compiler will see when you use the name of the variable.
[src:rust/ch03-01-variables-and-mutability] In effect, the second variable overshadows the first, taking any uses of the variable name to itself until either it itself is shadowed or the scope ends.
[src:rust/ch03-01-variables-and-mutability] This program first binds `x` to a value of `5`.
[src:rust/ch03-01-variables-and-mutability] Then, it creates a new variable `x` by repeating `let x =`, taking the original value and adding `1` so that the value of `x` is `6`.
[src:rust/ch03-01-variables-and-mutability] Then, within an inner scope created with the curly brackets, the third `let` statement also shadows `x` and creates a new variable, multiplying the previous value by `2` to give `x` a value of `12`.
[src:rust/ch03-01-variables-and-mutability] When that scope is over, the inner shadowing ends and `x` returns to being `6`.
[src:rust/ch03-01-variables-and-mutability] Shadowing is different from marking a variable as `mut` because we’ll get a compile-time error if we accidentally try to reassign to this variable without using the `let` keyword.
[src:rust/ch03-01-variables-and-mutability] By using `let`, we can perform a few transformations on a value but have the variable be immutable after those transformations have completed.
[src:rust/ch03-01-variables-and-mutability] The other difference between `mut` and shadowing is that because we’re effectively creating a new variable when we use the `let` keyword again, we can change the type of the value but reuse the same name.
[src:rust/ch03-01-variables-and-mutability] The first `spaces` variable is a string type, and the second `spaces` variable is a number type.
[src:rust/ch03-01-variables-and-mutability] Shadowing thus spares us from having to come up with different names, such as `spaces_str` and `spaces_num`; instead, we can reuse the simpler `spaces` name.
[src:rust/ch03-01-variables-and-mutability] Now that we’ve explored how variables work, let’s look at more data types they can have.
[src:rust/ch03-02-data-types] Every value in Rust is of a certain *data type*, which tells Rust what kind of data is being specified so that it knows how to work with that data.
[src:rust/ch03-02-data-types] We’ll look at two data type subsets: scalar and compound.
[src:rust/ch03-02-data-types] Keep in mind that Rust is a *statically typed* language, which means that it must know the types of all variables at compile time.
[src:rust/ch03-02-data-types] The compiler can usually infer what type we want to use based on the value and how we use it.
[src:rust/ch03-02-data-types] You’ll see different type annotations for other data types.
[src:rust/ch03-02-data-types] A *scalar* type represents a single value.
[src:rust/ch03-02-data-types] Rust has four primary scalar types: integers, floating-point numbers, Booleans, and characters.
[src:rust/ch03-02-data-types] You may recognize these from other programming languages.
[src:rust/ch03-02-data-types] An *integer* is a number without a fractional component.
[src:rust/ch03-02-data-types] We used one integer type in Chapter 2, the `u32` type.
[src:rust/ch03-02-data-types] This type declaration indicates that the value it’s associated with should be an unsigned integer (signed integer types start with `i` instead of `u`) that takes up 32 bits of space.
[src:rust/ch03-02-data-types] Table 3-1 shows the built-in integer types in Rust.
[src:rust/ch03-02-data-types] We can use any of these variants to declare the type of an integer value.
[src:rust/ch03-02-data-types] Each variant can be either signed or unsigned and has an explicit size.
[src:rust/ch03-02-data-types] *Signed* and *unsigned* refer to whether it’s possible for the number to be negative—in other words, whether the number needs to have a sign with it (signed) or whether it will only ever be positive and can therefore be represented without a sign (unsigned).
[src:rust/ch03-02-data-types] It’s like writing numbers on paper: When the sign matters, a number is shown with a plus sign or a minus sign; however, when it’s safe to assume the number is positive, it’s shown with no sign.
[src:rust/ch03-02-data-types] Signed numbers are stored using two’s complement representation.
[src:rust/ch03-02-data-types] Each signed variant can store numbers from −(2n − 1) to 2n − 1 − 1 inclusive, where *n* is the number of bits that variant uses.
[src:rust/ch03-02-data-types] Unsigned variants can store numbers from 0 to 2n − 1, so a `u8` can store numbers from 0 to 28 − 1, which equals 0 to 255.
[src:rust/ch03-02-data-types] Additionally, the `isize` and `usize` types depend on the architecture of the computer your program is running on: 64 bits if you’re on a 64-bit architecture and 32 bits if you’re on a 32-bit architecture.
[src:rust/ch03-02-data-types] You can write integer literals in any of the forms shown in Table 3-2.
[src:rust/ch03-02-data-types] Note that number literals that can be multiple numeric types allow a type suffix, such as `57u8`, to designate the type.
[src:rust/ch03-02-data-types] Number literals can also use `_` as a visual separator to make the number easier to read, such as `1_000`, which will have the same value as if you had specified `1000`.
[src:rust/ch03-02-data-types] So how do you know which type of integer to use?
[src:rust/ch03-02-data-types] If you’re unsure, Rust’s defaults are generally good places to start: Integer types default to `i32`.
[src:rust/ch03-02-data-types] The primary situation in which you’d use `isize` or `usize` is when indexing some sort of collection.
[src:rust/ch03-02-data-types] Let’s say you have a variable of type `u8` that can hold values between 0 and 255.
[src:rust/ch03-02-data-types] If you try to change the variable to a value outside that range, such as 256, *integer overflow* will occur, which can result in one of two behaviors.
[src:rust/ch03-02-data-types] When you’re compiling in debug mode, Rust includes checks for integer overflow that cause your program to *panic* at runtime if this behavior occurs.
[src:rust/ch03-02-data-types] Rust uses the term *panicking* when a program exits with an error; we’ll discuss panics in more depth in the “Unrecoverable Errors with `panic!`” section in Chapter 9.
[src:rust/ch03-02-data-types] When you’re compiling in release mode with the `--release` flag, Rust does *not* include checks for integer overflow that cause panics.
[src:rust/ch03-02-data-types] Instead, if overflow occurs, Rust performs *two’s complement wrapping*.
[src:rust/ch03-02-data-types] In short, values greater than the maximum value the type can hold “wrap around” to the minimum of the values the type can hold.
[src:rust/ch03-02-data-types] In the case of a `u8`, the value 256 becomes 0, the value 257 becomes 1, and so on.
[src:rust/ch03-02-data-types] The program won’t panic, but the variable will have a value that probably isn’t what you were expecting it to have.
[src:rust/ch03-02-data-types] Relying on integer overflow’s wrapping behavior is considered an error.
[src:rust/ch03-02-data-types] Rust also has two primitive types for *floating-point numbers*, which are numbers with decimal points.
[src:rust/ch03-02-data-types] Rust’s floating-point types are `f32` and `f64`, which are 32 bits and 64 bits in size, respectively.
[src:rust/ch03-02-data-types] The default type is `f64` because on modern CPUs, it’s roughly the same speed as `f32` but is capable of more precision.
[src:rust/ch03-02-data-types] Floating-point numbers are represented according to the IEEE-754 standard.
[src:rust/ch03-02-data-types] Rust supports the basic mathematical operations you’d expect for all the number types: addition, subtraction, multiplication, division, and remainder.
[src:rust/ch03-02-data-types] Integer division truncates toward zero to the nearest integer.
[src:rust/ch03-02-data-types] Each expression in these statements uses a mathematical operator and evaluates to a single value, which is then bound to a variable.
[src:rust/ch03-02-data-types] Appendix B contains a list of all operators that Rust provides.
[src:rust/ch03-02-data-types] As in most other programming languages, a Boolean type in Rust has two possible values: `true` and `false`.
[src:rust/ch03-02-data-types] The Boolean type in Rust is specified using `bool`.
[src:rust/ch03-02-data-types] The main way to use Boolean values is through conditionals, such as an `if` expression.
[src:rust/ch03-02-data-types] We’ll cover how `if` expressions work in Rust in the “Control Flow” section.
[src:rust/ch03-02-data-types] Rust’s `char` type is the language’s most primitive alphabetic type.
[src:rust/ch03-02-data-types] Note that we specify `char` literals with single quotation marks, as opposed to string literals, which use double quotation marks.
[src:rust/ch03-02-data-types] Rust’s `char` type is 4 bytes in size and represents a Unicode scalar value, which means it can represent a lot more than just ASCII.
[src:rust/ch03-02-data-types] Accented letters; Chinese, Japanese, and Korean characters; emojis; and zero-width spaces are all valid `char` values in Rust.
[src:rust/ch03-02-data-types] Unicode scalar values range from `U+0000` to `U+D7FF` and `U+E000` to `U+10FFFF` inclusive.
[src:rust/ch03-02-data-types] However, a “character” isn’t really a concept in Unicode, so your human intuition for what a “character” is may not match up with what a `char` is in Rust.
[src:rust/ch03-02-data-types] We’ll discuss this topic in detail in “Storing UTF-8 Encoded Text with Strings” in Chapter 8.
[src:rust/ch03-02-data-types] A *tuple* is a general way of grouping together a number of values with a variety of types into one compound type.
[src:rust/ch03-02-data-types] Tuples have a fixed length: Once declared, they cannot grow or shrink in size.
[src:rust/ch03-02-data-types] We create a tuple by writing a comma-separated list of values inside parentheses.
[src:rust/ch03-02-data-types] Each position in the tuple has a type, and the types of the different values in the tuple don’t have to be the same.
[src:rust/ch03-02-data-types] The variable `tup` binds to the entire tuple because a tuple is considered a single compound element.
[src:rust/ch03-02-data-types] This program first creates a tuple and binds it to the variable `tup`.
[src:rust/ch03-02-data-types] It then uses a pattern with `let` to take `tup` and turn it into three separate variables, `x`, `y`, and `z`.
[src:rust/ch03-02-data-types] This is called *destructuring* because it breaks the single tuple into three parts.
[src:rust/ch03-02-data-types] Finally, the program prints the value of `y`, which is `6.4`.
[src:rust/ch03-02-data-types] We can also access a tuple element directly by using a period (`.`) followed by the index of the value we want to access.
[src:rust/ch03-02-data-types] This program creates the tuple `x` and then accesses each element of the tuple using their respective indices.
[src:rust/ch03-02-data-types] As with most programming languages, the first index in a tuple is 0.
[src:rust/ch03-02-data-types] The tuple without any values has a special name, *unit*.
[src:rust/ch03-02-data-types] This value and its corresponding type are both written `()` and represent an empty value or an empty return type.
[src:rust/ch03-02-data-types] Expressions implicitly return the unit value if they don’t return any other value.
[src:rust/ch03-02-data-types] Another way to have a collection of multiple values is with an *array*.
[src:rust/ch03-02-data-types] Unlike a tuple, every element of an array must have the same type.
[src:rust/ch03-02-data-types] Unlike arrays in some other languages, arrays in Rust have a fixed length.
[src:rust/ch03-02-data-types] Arrays are useful when you want your data allocated on the stack, the same as the other types we have seen so far, rather than the heap (we will discuss the stack and the heap more in Chapter 4) or when you want to ensure that you always have a fixed number of elements.
[src:rust/ch03-02-data-types] An array isn’t as flexible as the vector type, though.
[src:rust/ch03-02-data-types] A vector is a similar collection type provided by the standard library that *is* allowed to grow or shrink in size because its contents live on the heap.
[src:rust/ch03-02-data-types] If you’re unsure whether to use an array or a vector, chances are you should use a vector.
[src:rust/ch03-02-data-types] Chapter 8 discusses vectors in more detail.
[src:rust/ch03-02-data-types] However, arrays are more useful when you know the number of elements will not need to change.
[src:rust/ch03-02-data-types] Here, `i32` is the type of each element.
[src:rust/ch03-02-data-types] After the semicolon, the number `5` indicates the array contains five elements.
[src:rust/ch03-02-data-types] The array named `a` will contain `5` elements that will all be set to the value `3` initially.
[src:rust/ch03-02-data-types] This is the same as writing `let a = [3, 3, 3, 3, 3];` but in a more concise way.
[src:rust/ch03-02-data-types] An array is a single chunk of memory of a known, fixed size that can be allocated on the stack.
[src:rust/ch03-02-data-types] In this example, the variable named `first` will get the value `1` because that is the value at index `[0]` in the array.
[src:rust/ch03-02-data-types] The variable named `second` will get the value `2` from index `[1]` in the array.
[src:rust/ch03-02-data-types] Let’s see what happens if you try to access an element of an array that is past the end of the array.
[src:rust/ch03-02-data-types] If you run this code using `cargo run` and enter `0`, `1`, `2`, `3`, or `4`, the program will print out the corresponding value at that index in the array.
[src:rust/ch03-02-data-types] The program resulted in a runtime error at the point of using an invalid value in the indexing operation.
[src:rust/ch03-02-data-types] The program exited with an error message and didn’t execute the final `println!` statement.
[src:rust/ch03-02-data-types] When you attempt to access an element using indexing, Rust will check that the index you’ve specified is less than the array length.
[src:rust/ch03-02-data-types] If the index is greater than or equal to the length, Rust will panic.
[src:rust/ch03-02-data-types] This check has to happen at runtime, especially in this case, because the compiler can’t possibly know what value a user will enter when they run the code later.
[src:rust/ch03-02-data-types] This is an example of Rust’s memory safety principles in action.
[src:rust/ch03-02-data-types] In many low-level languages, this kind of check is not done, and when you provide an incorrect index, invalid memory can be accessed.
[src:rust/ch03-02-data-types] Rust protects you against this kind of error by immediately exiting instead of allowing the memory access and continuing.
[src:rust/ch03-02-data-types] Chapter 9 discusses more of Rust’s error handling and how you can write readable, safe code that neither panics nor allows invalid memory access.
[src:rust/ch03-03-how-functions-work] You’ve already seen one of the most important functions in the language: the `main` function, which is the entry point of many programs.
[src:rust/ch03-03-how-functions-work] You’ve also seen the `fn` keyword, which allows you to declare new functions.
[src:rust/ch03-03-how-functions-work] Rust code uses *snake case* as the conventional style for function and variable names, in which all letters are lowercase and underscores separate words.
[src:rust/ch03-03-how-functions-work] We define a function in Rust by entering `fn` followed by a function name and a set of parentheses.
[src:rust/ch03-03-how-functions-work] The curly brackets tell the compiler where the function body begins and ends.
[src:rust/ch03-03-how-functions-work] We can call any function we’ve defined by entering its name followed by a set of parentheses.
[src:rust/ch03-03-how-functions-work] Because `another_function` is defined in the program, it can be called from inside the `main` function.
[src:rust/ch03-03-how-functions-work] Note that we defined `another_function` *after* the `main` function in the source code; we could have defined it before as well.
[src:rust/ch03-03-how-functions-work] Rust doesn’t care where you define your functions, only that they’re defined somewhere in a scope that can be seen by the caller.
[src:rust/ch03-03-how-functions-work] Let’s start a new binary project named *functions* to explore functions further.
[src:rust/ch03-03-how-functions-work] Place the `another_function` example in *src/main.rs* and run it.
[src:rust/ch03-03-how-functions-work] The lines execute in the order in which they appear in the `main` function.
[src:rust/ch03-03-how-functions-work] First the “Hello, world!” message prints, and then `another_function` is called and its message is printed.
[src:rust/ch03-03-how-functions-work] We can define functions to have *parameters*, which are special variables that are part of a function’s signature.
[src:rust/ch03-03-how-functions-work] When a function has parameters, you can provide it with concrete values for those parameters.
[src:rust/ch03-03-how-functions-work] Technically, the concrete values are called *arguments*, but in casual conversation, people tend to use the words *parameter* and *argument* interchangeably for either the variables in a function’s definition or the concrete values passed in when you call a function.
[src:rust/ch03-03-how-functions-work] The declaration of `another_function` has one parameter named `x`.
[src:rust/ch03-03-how-functions-work] When we pass `5` in to `another_function`, the `println!` macro puts `5` where the pair of curly brackets containing `x` was in the format string.
[src:rust/ch03-03-how-functions-work] In function signatures, you *must* declare the type of each parameter.
[src:rust/ch03-03-how-functions-work] This is a deliberate decision in Rust’s design: Requiring type annotations in function definitions means the compiler almost never needs you to use them elsewhere in the code to figure out what type you mean.
[src:rust/ch03-03-how-functions-work] The compiler is also able to give more-helpful error messages if it knows what types the function expects.
[src:rust/ch03-03-how-functions-work] This example creates a function named `print_labeled_measurement` with two parameters.
[src:rust/ch03-03-how-functions-work] The first parameter is named `value` and is an `i32`.
[src:rust/ch03-03-how-functions-work] The second is named `unit_label` and is type `char`.
[src:rust/ch03-03-how-functions-work] The function then prints text containing both the `value` and the `unit_label`.
[src:rust/ch03-03-how-functions-work] Because we called the function with `5` as the value for `value` and `'h'` as the value for `unit_label`, the program output contains those values.
[src:rust/ch03-03-how-functions-work] Function bodies are made up of a series of statements optionally ending in an expression.
[src:rust/ch03-03-how-functions-work] So far, the functions we’ve covered haven’t included an ending expression, but you have seen an expression as part of a statement.
[src:rust/ch03-03-how-functions-work] Because Rust is an expression-based language, this is an important distinction to understand.
[src:rust/ch03-03-how-functions-work] Other languages don’t have the same distinctions, so let’s look at what statements and expressions are and how their differences affect the bodies of functions.
[src:rust/ch03-03-how-functions-work] We’ve actually already used statements and expressions.
[src:rust/ch03-03-how-functions-work] Creating a variable and assigning a value to it with the `let` keyword is a statement.
[src:rust/ch03-03-how-functions-work] In Listing 3-1, `let y = 6;` is a statement.
[src:rust/ch03-03-how-functions-work] Function definitions are also statements; the entire preceding example is a statement in itself.
[src:rust/ch03-03-how-functions-work] The `let y = 6` statement does not return a value, so there isn’t anything for `x` to bind to.
[src:rust/ch03-03-how-functions-work] This is different from what happens in other languages, such as C and Ruby, where the assignment returns the value of the assignment.
[src:rust/ch03-03-how-functions-work] In those languages, you can write `x = y = 6` and have both `x` and `y` have the value `6`; that is not the case in Rust.
[src:rust/ch03-03-how-functions-work] Expressions evaluate to a value and make up most of the rest of the code that you’ll write in Rust.
[src:rust/ch03-03-how-functions-work] Consider a math operation, such as `5 + 6`, which is an expression that evaluates to the value `11`.
[src:rust/ch03-03-how-functions-work] Expressions can be part of statements: In Listing 3-1, the `6` in the statement `let y = 6;` is an expression that evaluates to the value `6`.
[src:rust/ch03-03-how-functions-work] is a block that, in this case, evaluates to `4`.
[src:rust/ch03-03-how-functions-work] That value gets bound to `y` as part of the `let` statement.
[src:rust/ch03-03-how-functions-work] Note the `x + 1` line without a semicolon at the end, which is unlike most of the lines you’ve seen so far.
[src:rust/ch03-03-how-functions-work] Expressions do not include ending semicolons.
[src:rust/ch03-03-how-functions-work] If you add a semicolon to the end of an expression, you turn it into a statement, and it will then not return a value.
[src:rust/ch03-03-how-functions-work] Keep this in mind as you explore function return values and expressions next.
[src:rust/ch03-03-how-functions-work] Functions can return values to the code that calls them.
[src:rust/ch03-03-how-functions-work] We don’t name return values, but we must declare their type after an arrow (`->`).
[src:rust/ch03-03-how-functions-work] In Rust, the return value of the function is synonymous with the value of the final expression in the block of the body of a function.
[src:rust/ch03-03-how-functions-work] You can return early from a function by using the `return` keyword and specifying a value, but most functions return the last expression implicitly.
[src:rust/ch03-03-how-functions-work] There are no function calls, macros, or even `let` statements in the `five` function—just the number `5` by itself.
[src:rust/ch03-03-how-functions-work] That’s a perfectly valid function in Rust.
[src:rust/ch03-03-how-functions-work] Note that the function’s return type is specified too, as `-> i32`.
[src:rust/ch03-03-how-functions-work] The `5` in `five` is the function’s return value, which is why the return type is `i32`.
[src:rust/ch03-03-how-functions-work] There are two important bits: First, the line `let x = five();` shows that we’re using the return value of a function to initialize a variable.
[src:rust/ch03-03-how-functions-work] Second, the `five` function has no parameters and defines the type of the return value, but the body of the function is a lonely `5` with no semicolon because it’s an expression whose value we want to return.
[src:rust/ch03-03-how-functions-work] Running this code will print `The value of x is: 6`.
[src:rust/ch03-03-how-functions-work] But what happens if we place a semicolon at the end of the line containing `x + 1`, changing it from an expression to a statement?
[src:rust/ch03-03-how-functions-work] The main error message, `mismatched types`, reveals the core issue with this code.
[src:rust/ch03-03-how-functions-work] The definition of the function `plus_one` says that it will return an `i32`, but statements don’t evaluate to a value, which is expressed by `()`, the unit type.
[src:rust/ch03-03-how-functions-work] Therefore, nothing is returned, which contradicts the function definition and results in an error.
[src:rust/ch03-03-how-functions-work] In this output, Rust provides a message to possibly help rectify this issue: It suggests removing the semicolon, which would fix the error.
[src:rust/ch04-01-what-is-ownership] Because ownership is a new concept for many programmers, it does take some time to get used to.
[src:rust/ch04-01-what-is-ownership] The good news is that the more experienced you become with Rust and the rules of the ownership system, the easier you’ll find it to naturally develop code that is safe and efficient.
[src:rust/ch04-01-what-is-ownership] When you understand ownership, you’ll have a solid foundation for understanding the features that make Rust unique.
[src:rust/ch04-01-what-is-ownership] In this chapter, you’ll learn ownership by working through some examples that focus on a very common data structure: strings.
[src:rust/ch04-01-what-is-ownership] Many programming languages don’t require you to think about the stack and the heap very often.
[src:rust/ch04-01-what-is-ownership] But in a systems programming language like Rust, whether a value is on the stack or the heap affects how the language behaves and why you have to make certain decisions.
[src:rust/ch04-01-what-is-ownership] Parts of ownership will be described in relation to the stack and the heap later in this chapter, so here is a brief explanation in preparation.
[src:rust/ch04-01-what-is-ownership] Both the stack and the heap are parts of memory available to your code to use at runtime, but they are structured in different ways.
[src:rust/ch04-01-what-is-ownership] The stack stores values in the order it gets them and removes the values in the opposite order.
[src:rust/ch04-01-what-is-ownership] This is referred to as *last in, first out (LIFO)*.
[src:rust/ch04-01-what-is-ownership] Think of a stack of plates: When you add more plates, you put them on top of the pile, and when you need a plate, you take one off the top.
[src:rust/ch04-01-what-is-ownership] Adding or removing plates from the middle or bottom wouldn’t work as well!
[src:rust/ch04-01-what-is-ownership] Adding data is called *pushing onto the stack*, and removing data is called *popping off the stack*.
[src:rust/ch04-01-what-is-ownership] All data stored on the stack must have a known, fixed size.
[src:rust/ch04-01-what-is-ownership] Data with an unknown size at compile time or a size that might change must be stored on the heap instead.
[src:rust/ch04-01-what-is-ownership] The heap is less organized: When you put data on the heap, you request a certain amount of space.
[src:rust/ch04-01-what-is-ownership] The memory allocator finds an empty spot in the heap that is big enough, marks it as being in use, and returns a *pointer*, which is the address of that location.
[src:rust/ch04-01-what-is-ownership] This process is called *allocating on the heap* and is sometimes abbreviated as just *allocating* (pushing values onto the stack is not considered allocating).
[src:rust/ch04-01-what-is-ownership] Because the pointer to the heap is a known, fixed size, you can store the pointer on the stack, but when you want the actual data, you must follow the pointer.
[src:rust/ch04-01-what-is-ownership] When you enter, you state the number of people in your group, and the host finds an empty table that fits everyone and leads you there.
[src:rust/ch04-01-what-is-ownership] If someone in your group comes late, they can ask where you’ve been seated to find you.
[src:rust/ch04-01-what-is-ownership] Pushing to the stack is faster than allocating on the heap because the allocator never has to search for a place to store new data; that location is always at the top of the stack.
[src:rust/ch04-01-what-is-ownership] Comparatively, allocating space on the heap requires more work because the allocator must first find a big enough space to hold the data and then perform bookkeeping to prepare for the next allocation.
[src:rust/ch04-01-what-is-ownership] Accessing data in the heap is generally slower than accessing data on the stack because you have to follow a pointer to get there.
[src:rust/ch04-01-what-is-ownership] Contemporary processors are faster if they jump around less in memory.
[src:rust/ch04-01-what-is-ownership] Continuing the analogy, consider a server at a restaurant taking orders from many tables.
[src:rust/ch04-01-what-is-ownership] It’s most efficient to get all the orders at one table before moving on to the next table.
[src:rust/ch04-01-what-is-ownership] Taking an order from table A, then an order from table B, then one from A again, and then one from B again would be a much slower process.
[src:rust/ch04-01-what-is-ownership] By the same token, a processor can usually do its job better if it works on data that’s close to other data (as it is on the stack) rather than farther away (as it can be on the heap).
[src:rust/ch04-01-what-is-ownership] When your code calls a function, the values passed into the function (including, potentially, pointers to data on the heap) and the function’s local variables get pushed onto the stack.
[src:rust/ch04-01-what-is-ownership] When the function is over, those values get popped off the stack.
[src:rust/ch04-01-what-is-ownership] Keeping track of what parts of code are using what data on the heap, minimizing the amount of duplicate data on the heap, and cleaning up unused data on the heap so that you don’t run out of space are all problems that ownership addresses.
[src:rust/ch04-01-what-is-ownership] Once you understand ownership, you won’t need to think about the stack and the heap very often.
[src:rust/ch04-01-what-is-ownership] But knowing that the main purpose of ownership is to manage heap data can help explain why it works the way it does.
[src:rust/ch04-01-what-is-ownership] First, let’s take a look at the ownership rules.
[src:rust/ch04-01-what-is-ownership] Now that we’re past basic Rust syntax, we won’t include all the `fn main() {` code in the examples, so if you’re following along, make sure to put the following examples inside a `main` function manually.
[src:rust/ch04-01-what-is-ownership] As a result, our examples will be a bit more concise, letting us focus on the actual details rather than boilerplate code.
[src:rust/ch04-01-what-is-ownership] As a first example of ownership, we’ll look at the scope of some variables.
[src:rust/ch04-01-what-is-ownership] A *scope* is the range within a program for which an item is valid.
[src:rust/ch04-01-what-is-ownership] The variable `s` refers to a string literal, where the value of the string is hardcoded into the text of our program.
[src:rust/ch04-01-what-is-ownership] The variable is valid from the point at which it’s declared until the end of the current scope.
[src:rust/ch04-01-what-is-ownership] Listing 4-1 shows a program with comments annotating where the variable `s` would be valid.
[src:rust/ch04-01-what-is-ownership] At this point, the relationship between scopes and when variables are valid is similar to that in other programming languages.
[src:rust/ch04-01-what-is-ownership] Now we’ll build on top of this understanding by introducing the `String` type.
[src:rust/ch04-01-what-is-ownership] To illustrate the rules of ownership, we need a data type that is more complex than those we covered in the “Data Types” section of Chapter 3.
[src:rust/ch04-01-what-is-ownership] The types covered previously are of a known size, can be stored on the stack and popped off the stack when their scope is over, and can be quickly and trivially copied to make a new, independent instance if another part of code needs to use the same value in a different scope.
[src:rust/ch04-01-what-is-ownership] But we want to look at data that is stored on the heap and explore how Rust knows when to clean up that data, and the `String` type is a great example.
[src:rust/ch04-01-what-is-ownership] We’ll concentrate on the parts of `String` that relate to ownership.
[src:rust/ch04-01-what-is-ownership] These aspects also apply to other complex data types, whether they are provided by the standard library or created by you.
[src:rust/ch04-01-what-is-ownership] We’ll discuss non-ownership aspects of `String` in Chapter 8.
[src:rust/ch04-01-what-is-ownership] We’ve already seen string literals, where a string value is hardcoded into our program.
[src:rust/ch04-01-what-is-ownership] String literals are convenient, but they aren’t suitable for every situation in which we may want to use text.
[src:rust/ch04-01-what-is-ownership] Another is that not every string value can be known when we write our code: For example, what if we want to take user input and store it?
[src:rust/ch04-01-what-is-ownership] It is for these situations that Rust has the `String` type.
[src:rust/ch04-01-what-is-ownership] This type manages data allocated on the heap and as such is able to store an amount of text that is unknown to us at compile time.
[src:rust/ch04-01-what-is-ownership] The double colon `::` operator allows us to namespace this particular `from` function under the `String` type rather than using some sort of name like `string_from`.
[src:rust/ch04-01-what-is-ownership] We’ll discuss this syntax more in the “Methods” section of Chapter 5, and when we talk about namespacing with modules in “Paths for Referring to an Item in the Module Tree” in Chapter 7.
[src:rust/ch04-01-what-is-ownership] Why can `String` be mutated but literals cannot?
[src:rust/ch04-01-what-is-ownership] The difference is in how these two types deal with memory.
[src:rust/ch04-01-what-is-ownership] In the case of a string literal, we know the contents at compile time, so the text is hardcoded directly into the final executable.
[src:rust/ch04-01-what-is-ownership] This is why string literals are fast and efficient.
[src:rust/ch04-01-what-is-ownership] But these properties only come from the string literal’s immutability.
[src:rust/ch04-01-what-is-ownership] Unfortunately, we can’t put a blob of memory into the binary for each piece of text whose size is unknown at compile time and whose size might change while running the program.
[src:rust/ch04-01-what-is-ownership] With the `String` type, in order to support a mutable, growable piece of text, we need to allocate an amount of memory on the heap, unknown at compile time, to hold the contents.
[src:rust/ch04-01-what-is-ownership] That first part is done by us: When we call `String::from`, its implementation requests the memory it needs.
[src:rust/ch04-01-what-is-ownership] This is pretty much universal in programming languages.
[src:rust/ch04-01-what-is-ownership] In languages with a *garbage collector (GC)*, the GC keeps track of and cleans up memory that isn’t being used anymore, and we don’t need to think about it.
[src:rust/ch04-01-what-is-ownership] In most languages without a GC, it’s our responsibility to identify when memory is no longer being used and to call code to explicitly free it, just as we did to request it.
[src:rust/ch04-01-what-is-ownership] Doing this correctly has historically been a difficult programming problem.
[src:rust/ch04-01-what-is-ownership] If we do it too early, we’ll have an invalid variable.
[src:rust/ch04-01-what-is-ownership] We need to pair exactly one `allocate` with exactly one `free`.
[src:rust/ch04-01-what-is-ownership] Rust takes a different path: The memory is automatically returned once the variable that owns it goes out of scope.
[src:rust/ch04-01-what-is-ownership] There is a natural point at which we can return the memory our `String` needs to the allocator: when `s` goes out of scope.
[src:rust/ch04-01-what-is-ownership] When a variable goes out of scope, Rust calls a special function for us.
[src:rust/ch04-01-what-is-ownership] This function is called `drop`, and it’s where the author of `String` can put the code to return the memory.
[src:rust/ch04-01-what-is-ownership] Rust calls `drop` automatically at the closing curly bracket.
[src:rust/ch04-01-what-is-ownership] Note: In C++, this pattern of deallocating resources at the end of an item’s lifetime is sometimes called *Resource Acquisition Is Initialization (RAII)*.
[src:rust/ch04-01-what-is-ownership] The `drop` function in Rust will be familiar to you if you’ve used RAII patterns.
[src:rust/ch04-01-what-is-ownership] This pattern has a profound impact on the way Rust code is written.
[src:rust/ch04-01-what-is-ownership] It may seem simple right now, but the behavior of code can be unexpected in more complicated situations when we want to have multiple variables use the data we’ve allocated on the heap.
[src:rust/ch04-01-what-is-ownership] Let’s explore some of those situations now.
[src:rust/ch04-01-what-is-ownership] Multiple variables can interact with the same data in different ways in Rust.
[src:rust/ch04-01-what-is-ownership] Listing 4-2 shows an example using an integer.
[src:rust/ch04-01-what-is-ownership] We can probably guess what this is doing: “Bind the value `5` to `x`; then, make a copy of the value in `x` and bind it to `y`.” We now have two variables, `x` and `y`, and both equal `5`.
[src:rust/ch04-01-what-is-ownership] This is indeed what is happening, because integers are simple values with a known, fixed size, and these two `5` values are pushed onto the stack.
[src:rust/ch04-01-what-is-ownership] This looks very similar, so we might assume that the way it works would be the same: That is, the second line would make a copy of the value in `s1` and bind it to `s2`.
[src:rust/ch04-01-what-is-ownership] Take a look at Figure 4-1 to see what is happening to `String` under the covers.
[src:rust/ch04-01-what-is-ownership] A `String` is made up of three parts, shown on the left: a pointer to the memory that holds the contents of the string, a length, and a capacity.
[src:rust/ch04-01-what-is-ownership] This group of data is stored on the stack.
[src:rust/ch04-01-what-is-ownership] On the right is the memory on the heap that holds the contents.
[src:rust/ch04-01-what-is-ownership] (Two tables: the first table contains the representation of s1 on the stack, consisting of its length (5), capacity (5), and a pointer to the first value in the second table.
[src:rust/ch04-01-what-is-ownership] The length is how much memory, in bytes, the contents of the `String` are currently using.
[src:rust/ch04-01-what-is-ownership] The capacity is the total amount of memory, in bytes, that the `String` has received from the allocator.
[src:rust/ch04-01-what-is-ownership] The difference between length and capacity matters, but not in this context, so for now, it’s fine to ignore the capacity.
[src:rust/ch04-01-what-is-ownership] When we assign `s1` to `s2`, the `String` data is copied, meaning we copy the pointer, the length, and the capacity that are on the stack.
[src:rust/ch04-01-what-is-ownership] We do not copy the data on the heap that the pointer refers to.
[src:rust/ch04-01-what-is-ownership] In other words, the data representation in memory looks like Figure 4-2.
[src:rust/ch04-01-what-is-ownership] The representation does *not* look like Figure 4-3, which is what memory would look like if Rust instead copied the heap data as well.
[src:rust/ch04-01-what-is-ownership] If Rust did this, the operation `s2 = s1` could be very expensive in terms of runtime performance if the data on the heap were large.
[src:rust/ch04-01-what-is-ownership] Earlier, we said that when a variable goes out of scope, Rust automatically calls the `drop` function and cleans up the heap memory for that variable.
[src:rust/ch04-01-what-is-ownership] But Figure 4-2 shows both data pointers pointing to the same location.
[src:rust/ch04-01-what-is-ownership] This is a problem: When `s2` and `s1` go out of scope, they will both try to free the same memory.
[src:rust/ch04-01-what-is-ownership] This is known as a *double free* error and is one of the memory safety bugs we mentioned previously.
[src:rust/ch04-01-what-is-ownership] Freeing memory twice can lead to memory corruption, which can potentially lead to security vulnerabilities.
[src:rust/ch04-01-what-is-ownership] To ensure memory safety, after the line `let s2 = s1;`, Rust considers `s1` as no longer valid.
[src:rust/ch04-01-what-is-ownership] Therefore, Rust doesn’t need to free anything when `s1` goes out of scope.
[src:rust/ch04-01-what-is-ownership] If you’ve heard the terms *shallow copy* and *deep copy* while working with other languages, the concept of copying the pointer, length, and capacity without copying the data probably sounds like making a shallow copy.
[src:rust/ch04-01-what-is-ownership] But because Rust also invalidates the first variable, instead of being called a shallow copy, it’s known as a *move*.
[src:rust/ch04-01-what-is-ownership] In this example, we would say that `s1` was *moved* into `s2`.
[src:rust/ch04-01-what-is-ownership] So, what actually happens is shown in Figure 4-4.
[src:rust/ch04-01-what-is-ownership] (Three tables: tables s1 and s2 representing those strings on the stack, respectively, and both pointing to the same string data on the heap.
[src:rust/ch04-01-what-is-ownership] With only `s2` valid, when it goes out of scope it alone will free the memory, and we’re done.
[src:rust/ch04-01-what-is-ownership] In addition, there’s a design choice that’s implied by this: Rust will never automatically create “deep” copies of your data.
[src:rust/ch04-01-what-is-ownership] Therefore, any *automatic* copying can be assumed to be inexpensive in terms of runtime performance.
[src:rust/ch04-01-what-is-ownership] The inverse of this is true for the relationship between scoping, ownership, and memory being freed via the `drop` function as well.
[src:rust/ch04-01-what-is-ownership] When you assign a completely new value to an existing variable, Rust will call `drop` and free the original value’s memory immediately.
[src:rust/ch04-01-what-is-ownership] We initially declare a variable `s` and bind it to a `String` with the value `"hello"`.
[src:rust/ch04-01-what-is-ownership] Then, we immediately create a new `String` with the value `"ahoy"` and assign it to `s`.
[src:rust/ch04-01-what-is-ownership] At this point, nothing is referring to the original value on the heap at all.
[src:rust/ch04-01-what-is-ownership] The original string thus immediately goes out of scope.
[src:rust/ch04-01-what-is-ownership] Rust will run the `drop` function on it and its memory will be freed right away.
[src:rust/ch04-01-what-is-ownership] When we print the value at the end, it will be `"ahoy, world!"`.
[src:rust/ch04-01-what-is-ownership] If we *do* want to deeply copy the heap data of the `String`, not just the stack data, we can use a common method called `clone`.
[src:rust/ch04-01-what-is-ownership] We’ll discuss method syntax in Chapter 5, but because methods are a common feature in many programming languages, you’ve probably seen them before.
[src:rust/ch04-01-what-is-ownership] This works just fine and explicitly produces the behavior shown in Figure 4-3, where the heap data *does* get copied.
[src:rust/ch04-01-what-is-ownership] When you see a call to `clone`, you know that some arbitrary code is being executed and that code may be expensive.
[src:rust/ch04-01-what-is-ownership] It’s a visual indicator that something different is going on.
[src:rust/ch04-01-what-is-ownership] There’s another wrinkle we haven’t talked about yet.
[src:rust/ch04-01-what-is-ownership] But this code seems to contradict what we just learned: We don’t have a call to `clone`, but `x` is still valid and wasn’t moved into `y`.
[src:rust/ch04-01-what-is-ownership] The reason is that types such as integers that have a known size at compile time are stored entirely on the stack, so copies of the actual values are quick to make.
[src:rust/ch04-01-what-is-ownership] That means there’s no reason we would want to prevent `x` from being valid after we create the variable `y`.
[src:rust/ch04-01-what-is-ownership] In other words, there’s no difference between deep and shallow copying here, so calling `clone` wouldn’t do anything different from the usual shallow copying, and we can leave it out.
[src:rust/ch04-01-what-is-ownership] Rust has a special annotation called the `Copy` trait that we can place on types that are stored on the stack, as integers are (we’ll talk more about traits in Chapter 10).
[src:rust/ch04-01-what-is-ownership] If a type implements the `Copy` trait, variables that use it do not move, but rather are trivially copied, making them still valid after assignment to another variable.
[src:rust/ch04-01-what-is-ownership] Rust won’t let us annotate a type with `Copy` if the type, or any of its parts, has implemented the `Drop` trait.
[src:rust/ch04-01-what-is-ownership] If the type needs something special to happen when the value goes out of scope and we add the `Copy` annotation to that type, we’ll get a compile-time error.
[src:rust/ch04-01-what-is-ownership] To learn about how to add the `Copy` annotation to your type to implement the trait, see “Derivable Traits” in Appendix C.
[src:rust/ch04-01-what-is-ownership] So, what types implement the `Copy` trait?
[src:rust/ch04-01-what-is-ownership] You can check the documentation for the given type to be sure, but as a general rule, any group of simple scalar values can implement `Copy`, and nothing that requires allocation or is some form of resource can implement `Copy`.
[src:rust/ch04-01-what-is-ownership] The mechanics of passing a value to a function are similar to those when assigning a value to a variable.
[src:rust/ch04-01-what-is-ownership] Passing a variable to a function will move or copy, just as assignment does.
[src:rust/ch04-01-what-is-ownership] Listing 4-3 has an example with some annotations showing where variables go into and out of scope.
[src:rust/ch04-01-what-is-ownership] If we tried to use `s` after the call to `takes_ownership`, Rust would throw a compile-time error.
[src:rust/ch04-01-what-is-ownership] These static checks protect us from mistakes.
[src:rust/ch04-01-what-is-ownership] Try adding code to `main` that uses `s` and `x` to see where you can use them and where the ownership rules prevent you from doing so.
[src:rust/ch04-01-what-is-ownership] Returning values can also transfer ownership.
[src:rust/ch04-01-what-is-ownership] Listing 4-4 shows an example of a function that returns some value, with similar annotations as those in Listing 4-3.
[src:rust/ch04-01-what-is-ownership] The ownership of a variable follows the same pattern every time: Assigning a value to another variable moves it.
[src:rust/ch04-01-what-is-ownership] When a variable that includes data on the heap goes out of scope, the value will be cleaned up by `drop` unless ownership of the data has been moved to another variable.
[src:rust/ch04-01-what-is-ownership] While this works, taking ownership and then returning ownership with every function is a bit tedious.
[src:rust/ch04-01-what-is-ownership] What if we want to let a function use a value but not take ownership?
[src:rust/ch04-01-what-is-ownership] It’s quite annoying that anything we pass in also needs to be passed back if we want to use it again, in addition to any data resulting from the body of the function that we might want to return as well.
[src:rust/ch04-01-what-is-ownership] Rust does let us return multiple values using a tuple, as shown in Listing 4-5.
[src:rust/ch04-01-what-is-ownership] But this is too much ceremony and a lot of work for a concept that should be common.
[src:rust/ch04-01-what-is-ownership] Luckily for us, Rust has a feature for using a value without transferring ownership: references.
[src:rust/ch04-02-references-and-borrowing] The issue with the tuple code in Listing 4-5 is that we have to return the `String` to the calling function so that we can still use the `String` after the call to `calculate_length`, because the `String` was moved into `calculate_length`.
[src:rust/ch04-02-references-and-borrowing] Instead, we can provide a reference to the `String` value.
[src:rust/ch04-02-references-and-borrowing] A reference is like a pointer in that it’s an address we can follow to access the data stored at that address; that data is owned by some other variable.
[src:rust/ch04-02-references-and-borrowing] Unlike a pointer, a reference is guaranteed to point to a valid value of a particular type for the life of that reference.
[src:rust/ch04-02-references-and-borrowing] First, notice that all the tuple code in the variable declaration and the function return value is gone.
[src:rust/ch04-02-references-and-borrowing] Second, note that we pass `&s1` into `calculate_length` and, in its definition, we take `&String` rather than `String`.
[src:rust/ch04-02-references-and-borrowing] These ampersands represent references, and they allow you to refer to some value without taking ownership of it.
[src:rust/ch04-02-references-and-borrowing] (Three tables: the table for s contains only a pointer to the table for s1.
[src:rust/ch04-02-references-and-borrowing] Note: The opposite of referencing by using `&` is *dereferencing*, which is accomplished with the dereference operator, `*`.
[src:rust/ch04-02-references-and-borrowing] We’ll see some uses of the dereference operator in Chapter 8 and discuss details of dereferencing in Chapter 15.
[src:rust/ch04-02-references-and-borrowing] The `&s1` syntax lets us create a reference that *refers* to the value of `s1` but does not own it.
[src:rust/ch04-02-references-and-borrowing] Because the reference does not own it, the value it points to will not be dropped when the reference stops being used.
[src:rust/ch04-02-references-and-borrowing] Likewise, the signature of the function uses `&` to indicate that the type of the parameter `s` is a reference.
[src:rust/ch04-02-references-and-borrowing] The scope in which the variable `s` is valid is the same as any function parameter’s scope, but the value pointed to by the reference is not dropped when `s` stops being used, because `s` doesn’t have ownership.
[src:rust/ch04-02-references-and-borrowing] When functions have references as parameters instead of the actual values, we won’t need to return the values in order to give back ownership, because we never had ownership.
[src:rust/ch04-02-references-and-borrowing] We call the action of creating a reference *borrowing*.
[src:rust/ch04-02-references-and-borrowing] As in real life, if a person owns something, you can borrow it from them.
[src:rust/ch04-02-references-and-borrowing] When you’re done, you have to give it back.
[src:rust/ch04-02-references-and-borrowing] So, what happens if we try to modify something we’re borrowing?
[src:rust/ch04-02-references-and-borrowing] Just as variables are immutable by default, so are references.
[src:rust/ch04-02-references-and-borrowing] We’re not allowed to modify something we have a reference to.
[src:rust/ch04-02-references-and-borrowing] Then, we create a mutable reference with `&mut s` where we call the `change` function and update the function signature to accept a mutable reference with `some_string: &mut String`.
[src:rust/ch04-02-references-and-borrowing] This makes it very clear that the `change` function will mutate the value it borrows.
[src:rust/ch04-02-references-and-borrowing] Mutable references have one big restriction: If you have a mutable reference to a value, you can have no other references to that value.
[src:rust/ch04-02-references-and-borrowing] This error says that this code is invalid because we cannot borrow `s` as mutable more than once at a time.
[src:rust/ch04-02-references-and-borrowing] The first mutable borrow is in `r1` and must last until it’s used in the `println!`, but between the creation of that mutable reference and its usage, we tried to create another mutable reference in `r2` that borrows the same data as `r1`.
[src:rust/ch04-02-references-and-borrowing] The restriction preventing multiple mutable references to the same data at the same time allows for mutation but in a very controlled fashion.
[src:rust/ch04-02-references-and-borrowing] It’s something that new Rustaceans struggle with because most languages let you mutate whenever you’d like.
[src:rust/ch04-02-references-and-borrowing] The benefit of having this restriction is that Rust can prevent data races at compile time.
[src:rust/ch04-02-references-and-borrowing] Data races cause undefined behavior and can be difficult to diagnose and fix when you’re trying to track them down at runtime; Rust prevents this problem by refusing to compile code with data races!
[src:rust/ch04-02-references-and-borrowing] Rust enforces a similar rule for combining mutable and immutable references.
[src:rust/ch04-02-references-and-borrowing] We *also* cannot have a mutable reference while we have an immutable one to the same value.
[src:rust/ch04-02-references-and-borrowing] Users of an immutable reference don’t expect the value to suddenly change out from under them!
[src:rust/ch04-02-references-and-borrowing] However, multiple immutable references are allowed because no one who is just reading the data has the ability to affect anyone else’s reading of the data.
[src:rust/ch04-02-references-and-borrowing] Note that a reference’s scope starts from where it is introduced and continues through the last time that reference is used.
[src:rust/ch04-02-references-and-borrowing] The scopes of the immutable references `r1` and `r2` end after the `println!` where they are last used, which is before the mutable reference `r3` is created.
[src:rust/ch04-02-references-and-borrowing] These scopes don’t overlap, so this code is allowed: The compiler can tell that the reference is no longer being used at a point before the end of the scope.
[src:rust/ch04-02-references-and-borrowing] Even though borrowing errors may be frustrating at times, remember that it’s the Rust compiler pointing out a potential bug early (at compile time rather than at runtime) and showing you exactly where the problem is.
[src:rust/ch04-02-references-and-borrowing] Then, you don’t have to track down why your data isn’t what you thought it was.
[src:rust/ch04-02-references-and-borrowing] In languages with pointers, it’s easy to erroneously create a *dangling pointer*—a pointer that references a location in memory that may have been given to someone else—by freeing some memory while preserving a pointer to that memory.
[src:rust/ch04-02-references-and-borrowing] In Rust, by contrast, the compiler guarantees that references will never be dangling references: If you have a reference to some data, the compiler will ensure that the data will not go out of scope before the reference to the data does.
[src:rust/ch04-02-references-and-borrowing] This error message refers to a feature we haven’t covered yet: lifetimes.
[src:rust/ch04-02-references-and-borrowing] We’ll discuss lifetimes in detail in Chapter 10.
[src:rust/ch04-02-references-and-borrowing] Because `s` is created inside `dangle`, when the code of `dangle` is finished, `s` will be deallocated.
[src:rust/ch04-02-references-and-borrowing] But we tried to return a reference to it.
[src:rust/ch04-02-references-and-borrowing] That means this reference would be pointing to an invalid `String`.
[src:rust/ch04-02-references-and-borrowing] Ownership is moved out, and nothing is deallocated.
[src:rust/ch04-02-references-and-borrowing] Next, we’ll look at a different kind of reference: slices.
[src:rust/ch04-03-slices] Here’s a small programming problem: Write a function that takes a string of words separated by spaces and returns the first word it finds in that string.
[src:rust/ch04-03-slices] If the function doesn’t find a space in the string, the whole string must be one word, so the entire string should be returned.
[src:rust/ch04-03-slices] Note: For the purposes of introducing slices, we are assuming ASCII only in this section; a more thorough discussion of UTF-8 handling is in the “Storing UTF-8 Encoded Text with Strings” section of Chapter 8.
[src:rust/ch04-03-slices] The `first_word` function has a parameter of type `&String`.
[src:rust/ch04-03-slices] We don’t need ownership, so this is fine.
[src:rust/ch04-03-slices] (In idiomatic Rust, functions do not take ownership of their arguments unless they need to, and the reasons for that will become clear as we keep going.) But what should we return?
[src:rust/ch04-03-slices] We don’t really have a way to talk about *part* of a string.
[src:rust/ch04-03-slices] However, we could return the index of the end of the word, indicated by a space.
[src:rust/ch04-03-slices] Let’s try that, as shown in Listing 4-7.
[src:rust/ch04-03-slices] Because we need to go through the `String` element by element and check whether a value is a space, we’ll convert our `String` to an array of bytes using the `as_bytes` method.
[src:rust/ch04-03-slices] We’ll discuss iterators in more detail in Chapter 13.
[src:rust/ch04-03-slices] For now, know that `iter` is a method that returns each element in a collection and that `enumerate` wraps the result of `iter` and returns each element as part of a tuple instead.
[src:rust/ch04-03-slices] The first element of the tuple returned from `enumerate` is the index, and the second element is a reference to the element.
[src:rust/ch04-03-slices] This is a bit more convenient than calculating the index ourselves.
[src:rust/ch04-03-slices] Because the `enumerate` method returns a tuple, we can use patterns to destructure that tuple.
[src:rust/ch04-03-slices] We’ll be discussing patterns more in Chapter 6.
[src:rust/ch04-03-slices] In the `for` loop, we specify a pattern that has `i` for the index in the tuple and `&item` for the single byte in the tuple.
[src:rust/ch04-03-slices] Because we get a reference to the element from `.iter().enumerate()`, we use `&` in the pattern.
[src:rust/ch04-03-slices] Inside the `for` loop, we search for the byte that represents the space by using the byte literal syntax.
[src:rust/ch04-03-slices] If we find a space, we return the position.
[src:rust/ch04-03-slices] Otherwise, we return the length of the string by using `s.len()`.
[src:rust/ch04-03-slices] We now have a way to find out the index of the end of the first word in the string, but there’s a problem.
[src:rust/ch04-03-slices] We’re returning a `usize` on its own, but it’s only a meaningful number in the context of the `&String`.
[src:rust/ch04-03-slices] In other words, because it’s a separate value from the `String`, there’s no guarantee that it will still be valid in the future.
[src:rust/ch04-03-slices] Consider the program in Listing 4-8 that uses the `first_word` function from Listing 4-7.
[src:rust/ch04-03-slices] This program compiles without any errors and would also do so if we used `word` after calling `s.clear()`.
[src:rust/ch04-03-slices] Because `word` isn’t connected to the state of `s` at all, `word` still contains the value `5`.
[src:rust/ch04-03-slices] We could use that value `5` with the variable `s` to try to extract the first word out, but this would be a bug because the contents of `s` have changed since we saved `5` in `word`.
[src:rust/ch04-03-slices] Having to worry about the index in `word` getting out of sync with the data in `s` is tedious and error-prone!
[src:rust/ch04-03-slices] Managing these indices is even more brittle if we write a `second_word` function.
[src:rust/ch04-03-slices] Now we’re tracking a starting *and* an ending index, and we have even more values that were calculated from data in a particular state but aren’t tied to that state at all.
[src:rust/ch04-03-slices] We have three unrelated variables floating around that need to be kept in sync.
[src:rust/ch04-03-slices] Luckily, Rust has a solution to this problem: string slices.
[src:rust/ch04-03-slices] Rather than a reference to the entire `String`, `hello` is a reference to a portion of the `String`, specified in the extra `[0..5]` bit.
[src:rust/ch04-03-slices] We create slices using a range within square brackets by specifying `[starting_index..ending_index]`, where *`starting_index`* is the first position in the slice and *`ending_index`* is one more than the last position in the slice.
[src:rust/ch04-03-slices] Internally, the slice data structure stores the starting position and the length of the slice, which corresponds to *`ending_index`* minus *`starting_index`*.
[src:rust/ch04-03-slices] So, in the case of `let world = &s[6..11];`, `world` would be a slice that contains a pointer to the byte at index 6 of `s` with a length value of `5`.
[src:rust/ch04-03-slices] (Three tables: a table representing the stack data of s, which points to the byte at index 0 in a table of the string data "hello world" on the heap.
[src:rust/ch04-03-slices] With Rust’s `..` range syntax, if you want to start at index 0, you can drop the value before the two periods.
[src:rust/ch04-03-slices] By the same token, if your slice includes the last byte of the `String`, you can drop the trailing number.
[src:rust/ch04-03-slices] You can also drop both values to take a slice of the entire string.
[src:rust/ch04-03-slices] Note: String slice range indices must occur at valid UTF-8 character boundaries.
[src:rust/ch04-03-slices] If you attempt to create a string slice in the middle of a multibyte character, your program will exit with an error.
[src:rust/ch04-03-slices] With all this information in mind, let’s rewrite `first_word` to return a slice.
[src:rust/ch04-03-slices] We get the index for the end of the word the same way we did in Listing 4-7, by looking for the first occurrence of a space.
[src:rust/ch04-03-slices] When we find a space, we return a string slice using the start of the string and the index of the space as the starting and ending indices.
[src:rust/ch04-03-slices] Now when we call `first_word`, we get back a single value that is tied to the underlying data.
[src:rust/ch04-03-slices] The value is made up of a reference to the starting point of the slice and the number of elements in the slice.
[src:rust/ch04-03-slices] We now have a straightforward API that’s much harder to mess up because the compiler will ensure that the references into the `String` remain valid.
[src:rust/ch04-03-slices] Remember the bug in the program in Listing 4-8, when we got the index to the end of the first word but then cleared the string so our index was invalid?
[src:rust/ch04-03-slices] That code was logically incorrect but didn’t show any immediate errors.
[src:rust/ch04-03-slices] The problems would show up later if we kept trying to use the first word index with an emptied string.
[src:rust/ch04-03-slices] Slices make this bug impossible and let us know much sooner that we have a problem with our code.
[src:rust/ch04-03-slices] Recall from the borrowing rules that if we have an immutable reference to something, we cannot also take a mutable reference.
[src:rust/ch04-03-slices] Because `clear` needs to truncate the `String`, it needs to get a mutable reference.
[src:rust/ch04-03-slices] The `println!` after the call to `clear` uses the reference in `word`, so the immutable reference must still be active at that point.
[src:rust/ch04-03-slices] Rust disallows the mutable reference in `clear` and the immutable reference in `word` from existing at the same time, and compilation fails.
[src:rust/ch04-03-slices] Not only has Rust made our API easier to use, but it has also eliminated an entire class of errors at compile time!
[src:rust/ch04-03-slices] Recall that we talked about string literals being stored inside the binary.
[src:rust/ch04-03-slices] The type of `s` here is `&str`: It’s a slice pointing to that specific point of the binary.
[src:rust/ch04-03-slices] This is also why string literals are immutable; `&str` is an immutable reference.
[src:rust/ch04-03-slices] A more experienced Rustacean would write the signature shown in Listing 4-9 instead because it allows us to use the same function on both `&String` values and `&str` values.
[src:rust/ch04-03-slices] If we have a string slice, we can pass that directly.
[src:rust/ch04-03-slices] If we have a `String`, we can pass a slice of the `String` or a reference to the `String`.
[src:rust/ch04-03-slices] This flexibility takes advantage of deref coercions, a feature we will cover in the “Using Deref Coercions in Functions and Methods” section of Chapter 15.
[src:rust/ch04-03-slices] String slices, as you might imagine, are specific to strings.
[src:rust/ch04-03-slices] But there’s a more general slice type too.
[src:rust/ch04-03-slices] Just as we might want to refer to part of a string, we might want to refer to part of an array.
[src:rust/ch04-03-slices] It works the same way as string slices do, by storing a reference to the first element and a length.
[src:rust/ch04-03-slices] You’ll use this kind of slice for all sorts of other collections.
[src:rust/ch04-03-slices] We’ll discuss these collections in detail when we talk about vectors in Chapter 8.
[src:rust/ch04-03-slices] The concepts of ownership, borrowing, and slices ensure memory safety in Rust programs at compile time.
[src:rust/ch04-03-slices] The Rust language gives you control over your memory usage in the same way as other systems programming languages.
[src:rust/ch04-03-slices] But having the owner of data automatically clean up that data when the owner goes out of scope means you don’t have to write and debug extra code to get this control.
[src:rust/ch04-03-slices] Ownership affects how lots of other parts of Rust work, so we’ll talk about these concepts further throughout the rest of the book.
[src:rust/ch04-03-slices] Let’s move on to Chapter 5 and look at grouping pieces of data together in a `struct`.
[src:rust/ch05-01-defining-structs] Structs are similar to tuples, discussed in “The Tuple Type” section, in that both hold multiple related values.
[src:rust/ch05-01-defining-structs] Like tuples, the pieces of a struct can be different types.
[src:rust/ch05-01-defining-structs] Unlike with tuples, in a struct you’ll name each piece of data so it’s clear what the values mean.
[src:rust/ch05-01-defining-structs] Adding these names means that structs are more flexible than tuples: You don’t have to rely on the order of the data to specify or access the values of an instance.
[src:rust/ch05-01-defining-structs] To define a struct, we enter the keyword `struct` and name the entire struct.
[src:rust/ch05-01-defining-structs] A struct’s name should describe the significance of the pieces of data being grouped together.
[src:rust/ch05-01-defining-structs] Then, inside curly brackets, we define the names and types of the pieces of data, which we call *fields*.
[src:rust/ch05-01-defining-structs] For example, Listing 5-1 shows a struct that stores information about a user account.
[src:rust/ch05-01-defining-structs] To use a struct after we’ve defined it, we create an *instance* of that struct by specifying concrete values for each of the fields.
[src:rust/ch05-01-defining-structs] We create an instance by stating the name of the struct and then add curly brackets containing *`key: value`* pairs, where the keys are the names of the fields and the values are the data we want to store in those fields.
[src:rust/ch05-01-defining-structs] We don’t have to specify the fields in the same order in which we declared them in the struct.
[src:rust/ch05-01-defining-structs] In other words, the struct definition is like a general template for the type, and instances fill in that template with particular data to create values of the type.
[src:rust/ch05-01-defining-structs] For example, we can declare a particular user as shown in Listing 5-2.
[src:rust/ch05-01-defining-structs] To get a specific value from a struct, we use dot notation.
[src:rust/ch05-01-defining-structs] For example, to access this user’s email address, we use `user1.email`.
[src:rust/ch05-01-defining-structs] If the instance is mutable, we can change a value by using the dot notation and assigning into a particular field.
[src:rust/ch05-01-defining-structs] Listing 5-3 shows how to change the value in the `email` field of a mutable `User` instance.
[src:rust/ch05-01-defining-structs] Note that the entire instance must be mutable; Rust doesn’t allow us to mark only certain fields as mutable.
[src:rust/ch05-01-defining-structs] As with any expression, we can construct a new instance of the struct as the last expression in the function body to implicitly return that new instance.
[src:rust/ch05-01-defining-structs] Listing 5-4 shows a `build_user` function that returns a `User` instance with the given email and username.
[src:rust/ch05-01-defining-structs] The `active` field gets the value `true`, and the `sign_in_count` gets a value of `1`.
[src:rust/ch05-01-defining-structs] It makes sense to name the function parameters with the same name as the struct fields, but having to repeat the `email` and `username` field names and variables is a bit tedious.
[src:rust/ch05-01-defining-structs] If the struct had more fields, repeating each name would get even more annoying.
[src:rust/ch05-01-defining-structs] Luckily, there’s a convenient shorthand!
[src:rust/ch05-01-defining-structs] Because the parameter names and the struct field names are exactly the same in Listing 5-4, we can use the *field init shorthand* syntax to rewrite `build_user` so that it behaves exactly the same but doesn’t have the repetition of `username` and `email`, as shown in Listing 5-5.
[src:rust/ch05-01-defining-structs] Here, we’re creating a new instance of the `User` struct, which has a field named `email`.
[src:rust/ch05-01-defining-structs] We want to set the `email` field’s value to the value in the `email` parameter of the `build_user` function.
[src:rust/ch05-01-defining-structs] Because the `email` field and the `email` parameter have the same name, we only need to write `email` rather than `email: email`.
[src:rust/ch05-01-defining-structs] It’s often useful to create a new instance of a struct that includes most of the values from another instance of the same type, but changes some of them.
[src:rust/ch05-01-defining-structs] You can do this using struct update syntax.
[src:rust/ch05-01-defining-structs] First, in Listing 5-6 we show how to create a new `User` instance in `user2` in the regular way, without the update syntax.
[src:rust/ch05-01-defining-structs] We set a new value for `email` but otherwise use the same values from `user1` that we created in Listing 5-2.
[src:rust/ch05-01-defining-structs] Using struct update syntax, we can achieve the same effect with less code, as shown in Listing 5-7.
[src:rust/ch05-01-defining-structs] The syntax `..` specifies that the remaining fields not explicitly set should have the same value as the fields in the given instance.
[src:rust/ch05-01-defining-structs] The code in Listing 5-7 also creates an instance in `user2` that has a different value for `email` but has the same values for the `username`, `active`, and `sign_in_count` fields from `user1`.
[src:rust/ch05-01-defining-structs] The `..user1` must come last to specify that any remaining fields should get their values from the corresponding fields in `user1`, but we can choose to specify values for as many fields as we want in any order, regardless of the order of the fields in the struct’s definition.
[src:rust/ch05-01-defining-structs] Note that the struct update syntax uses `=` like an assignment; this is because it moves the data, just as we saw in the “Variables and Data Interacting with Move” section.
[src:rust/ch05-01-defining-structs] In this example, we can no longer use `user1` after creating `user2` because the `String` in the `username` field of `user1` was moved into `user2`.
[src:rust/ch05-01-defining-structs] If we had given `user2` new `String` values for both `email` and `username`, and thus only used the `active` and `sign_in_count` values from `user1`, then `user1` would still be valid after creating `user2`.
[src:rust/ch05-01-defining-structs] Both `active` and `sign_in_count` are types that implement the `Copy` trait, so the behavior we discussed in the “Stack-Only Data: Copy” section would apply.
[src:rust/ch05-01-defining-structs] We can also still use `user1.email` in this example, because its value was not moved out of `user1`.
[src:rust/ch05-01-defining-structs] Rust also supports structs that look similar to tuples, called *tuple structs*.
[src:rust/ch05-01-defining-structs] Tuple structs have the added meaning the struct name provides but don’t have names associated with their fields; rather, they just have the types of the fields.
[src:rust/ch05-01-defining-structs] Tuple structs are useful when you want to give the whole tuple a name and make the tuple a different type from other tuples, and when naming each field as in a regular struct would be verbose or redundant.
[src:rust/ch05-01-defining-structs] To define a tuple struct, start with the `struct` keyword and the struct name followed by the types in the tuple.
[src:rust/ch05-01-defining-structs] Note that the `black` and `origin` values are different types because they’re instances of different tuple structs.
[src:rust/ch05-01-defining-structs] Each struct you define is its own type, even though the fields within the struct might have the same types.
[src:rust/ch05-01-defining-structs] For example, a function that takes a parameter of type `Color` cannot take a `Point` as an argument, even though both types are made up of three `i32` values.
[src:rust/ch05-01-defining-structs] Otherwise, tuple struct instances are similar to tuples in that you can destructure them into their individual pieces, and you can use a `.` followed by the index to access an individual value.
[src:rust/ch05-01-defining-structs] Unlike tuples, tuple structs require you to name the type of the struct when you destructure them.
[src:rust/ch05-01-defining-structs] For example, we would write `let Point(x, y, z) = origin;` to destructure the values in the `origin` point into variables named `x`, `y`, and `z`.
[src:rust/ch05-01-defining-structs] You can also define structs that don’t have any fields!
[src:rust/ch05-01-defining-structs] These are called *unit-like structs* because they behave similarly to `()`, the unit type that we mentioned in “The Tuple Type” section.
[src:rust/ch05-01-defining-structs] Unit-like structs can be useful when you need to implement a trait on some type but don’t have any data that you want to store in the type itself.
[src:rust/ch05-01-defining-structs] To define `AlwaysEqual`, we use the `struct` keyword, the name we want, and then a semicolon.
[src:rust/ch05-01-defining-structs] No need for curly brackets or parentheses!
[src:rust/ch05-01-defining-structs] Then, we can get an instance of `AlwaysEqual` in the `subject` variable in a similar way: using the name we defined, without any curly brackets or parentheses.
[src:rust/ch05-01-defining-structs] Imagine that later we’ll implement behavior for this type such that every instance of `AlwaysEqual` is always equal to every instance of any other type, perhaps to have a known result for testing purposes.
[src:rust/ch05-01-defining-structs] We wouldn’t need any data to implement that behavior!
[src:rust/ch05-01-defining-structs] You’ll see in Chapter 10 how to define traits and implement them on any type, including unit-like structs.
[src:rust/ch05-01-defining-structs] In the `User` struct definition in Listing 5-1, we used the owned `String` type rather than the `&str` string slice type.
[src:rust/ch05-01-defining-structs] This is a deliberate choice because we want each instance of this struct to own all of its data and for that data to be valid for as long as the entire struct is valid.
[src:rust/ch05-01-defining-structs] It’s also possible for structs to store references to data owned by something else, but to do so requires the use of *lifetimes*, a Rust feature that we’ll discuss in Chapter 10.
[src:rust/ch05-01-defining-structs] Lifetimes ensure that the data referenced by a struct is valid for as long as the struct is.
[src:rust/ch05-01-defining-structs] In Chapter 10, we’ll discuss how to fix these errors so that you can store references in structs, but for now, we’ll fix errors like these using owned types like `String` instead of references like `&str`.
[src:rust/ch06-01-defining-an-enum] Where structs give you a way of grouping together related fields and data, like a `Rectangle` with its `width` and `height`, enums give you a way of saying a value is one of a possible set of values.
[src:rust/ch06-01-defining-an-enum] For example, we may want to say that `Rectangle` is one of a set of possible shapes that also includes `Circle` and `Triangle`.
[src:rust/ch06-01-defining-an-enum] To do this, Rust allows us to encode these possibilities as an enum.
[src:rust/ch06-01-defining-an-enum] Let’s look at a situation we might want to express in code and see why enums are useful and more appropriate than structs in this case.
[src:rust/ch06-01-defining-an-enum] Currently, two major standards are used for IP addresses: version four and version six.
[src:rust/ch06-01-defining-an-enum] Because these are the only possibilities for an IP address that our program will come across, we can *enumerate* all possible variants, which is where enumeration gets its name.
[src:rust/ch06-01-defining-an-enum] Any IP address can be either a version four or a version six address, but not both at the same time.
[src:rust/ch06-01-defining-an-enum] That property of IP addresses makes the enum data structure appropriate because an enum value can only be one of its variants.
[src:rust/ch06-01-defining-an-enum] Both version four and version six addresses are still fundamentally IP addresses, so they should be treated as the same type when the code is handling situations that apply to any kind of IP address.
[src:rust/ch06-01-defining-an-enum] We can express this concept in code by defining an `IpAddrKind` enumeration and listing the possible kinds an IP address can be, `V4` and `V6`.
[src:rust/ch06-01-defining-an-enum] `IpAddrKind` is now a custom data type that we can use elsewhere in our code.
[src:rust/ch06-01-defining-an-enum] Note that the variants of the enum are namespaced under its identifier, and we use a double colon to separate the two.
[src:rust/ch06-01-defining-an-enum] This is useful because now both values `IpAddrKind::V4` and `IpAddrKind::V6` are of the same type: `IpAddrKind`.
[src:rust/ch06-01-defining-an-enum] Thinking more about our IP address type, at the moment we don’t have a way to store the actual IP address *data*; we only know what *kind* it is.
[src:rust/ch06-01-defining-an-enum] Given that you just learned about structs in Chapter 5, you might be tempted to tackle this problem with structs as shown in Listing 6-1.
[src:rust/ch06-01-defining-an-enum] Here, we’ve defined a struct `IpAddr` that has two fields: a `kind` field that is of type `IpAddrKind` (the enum we defined previously) and an `address` field of type `String`.
[src:rust/ch06-01-defining-an-enum] The first is `home`, and it has the value `IpAddrKind::V4` as its `kind` with associated address data of `127.0.0.1`.
[src:rust/ch06-01-defining-an-enum] It has the other variant of `IpAddrKind` as its `kind` value, `V6`, and has address `::1` associated with it.
[src:rust/ch06-01-defining-an-enum] We’ve used a struct to bundle the `kind` and `address` values together, so now the variant is associated with the value.
[src:rust/ch06-01-defining-an-enum] However, representing the same concept using just an enum is more concise: Rather than an enum inside a struct, we can put data directly into each enum variant.
[src:rust/ch06-01-defining-an-enum] We attach data to each variant of the enum directly, so there is no need for an extra struct.
[src:rust/ch06-01-defining-an-enum] Here, it’s also easier to see another detail of how enums work: The name of each enum variant that we define also becomes a function that constructs an instance of the enum.
[src:rust/ch06-01-defining-an-enum] That is, `IpAddr::V4()` is a function call that takes a `String` argument and returns an instance of the `IpAddr` type.
[src:rust/ch06-01-defining-an-enum] We automatically get this constructor function defined as a result of defining the enum.
[src:rust/ch06-01-defining-an-enum] There’s another advantage to using an enum rather than a struct: Each variant can have different types and amounts of associated data.
[src:rust/ch06-01-defining-an-enum] Version four IP addresses will always have four numeric components that will have values between 0 and 255.
[src:rust/ch06-01-defining-an-enum] If we wanted to store `V4` addresses as four `u8` values but still express `V6` addresses as one `String` value, we wouldn’t be able to with a struct.
[src:rust/ch06-01-defining-an-enum] We’ve shown several different ways to define data structures to store version four and version six IP addresses.
[src:rust/ch06-01-defining-an-enum] However, as it turns out, wanting to store IP addresses and encode which kind they are is so common that the standard library has a definition we can use!
[src:rust/ch06-01-defining-an-enum] Let’s look at how the standard library defines `IpAddr`.
[src:rust/ch06-01-defining-an-enum] This code illustrates that you can put any kind of data inside an enum variant: strings, numeric types, or structs, for example.
[src:rust/ch06-01-defining-an-enum] Also, standard library types are often not much more complicated than what you might come up with.
[src:rust/ch06-01-defining-an-enum] Note that even though the standard library contains a definition for `IpAddr`, we can still create and use our own definition without conflict because we haven’t brought the standard library’s definition into our scope.
[src:rust/ch06-01-defining-an-enum] We’ll talk more about bringing types into scope in Chapter 7.
[src:rust/ch06-01-defining-an-enum] Let’s look at another example of an enum in Listing 6-2: This one has a wide variety of types embedded in its variants.
[src:rust/ch06-01-defining-an-enum] Defining an enum with variants such as the ones in Listing 6-2 is similar to defining different kinds of struct definitions, except the enum doesn’t use the `struct` keyword and all the variants are grouped together under the `Message` type.
[src:rust/ch06-01-defining-an-enum] But if we used the different structs, each of which has its own type, we couldn’t as easily define a function to take any of these kinds of messages as we could with the `Message` enum defined in Listing 6-2, which is a single type.
[src:rust/ch06-01-defining-an-enum] There is one more similarity between enums and structs: Just as we’re able to define methods on structs using `impl`, we’re also able to define methods on enums.
[src:rust/ch06-01-defining-an-enum] The body of the method would use `self` to get the value that we called the method on.
[src:rust/ch06-01-defining-an-enum] In this example, we’ve created a variable `m` that has the value `Message::Write(String::from("hello"))`, and that is what `self` will be in the body of the `call` method when `m.call()` runs.
[src:rust/ch06-01-defining-an-enum] Let’s look at another enum in the standard library that is very common and useful: `Option`.
[src:rust/ch06-01-defining-an-enum] This section explores a case study of `Option`, which is another enum defined by the standard library.
[src:rust/ch06-01-defining-an-enum] The `Option` type encodes the very common scenario in which a value could be something, or it could be nothing.
[src:rust/ch06-01-defining-an-enum] For example, if you request the first item in a non-empty list, you would get a value.
[src:rust/ch06-01-defining-an-enum] If you request the first item in an empty list, you would get nothing.
[src:rust/ch06-01-defining-an-enum] Expressing this concept in terms of the type system means the compiler can check whether you’ve handled all the cases you should be handling; this functionality can prevent bugs that are extremely common in other programming languages.
[src:rust/ch06-01-defining-an-enum] Programming language design is often thought of in terms of which features you include, but the features you exclude are important too.
[src:rust/ch06-01-defining-an-enum] Rust doesn’t have the null feature that many other languages have.
[src:rust/ch06-01-defining-an-enum] *Null* is a value that means there is no value there.
[src:rust/ch06-01-defining-an-enum] In languages with null, variables can always be in one of two states: null or not-null.
[src:rust/ch06-01-defining-an-enum] The problem with null values is that if you try to use a null value as a not-null value, you’ll get an error of some kind.
[src:rust/ch06-01-defining-an-enum] Because this null or not-null property is pervasive, it’s extremely easy to make this kind of error.
[src:rust/ch06-01-defining-an-enum] However, the concept that null is trying to express is still a useful one: A null is a value that is currently invalid or absent for some reason.
[src:rust/ch06-01-defining-an-enum] The problem isn’t really with the concept but with the particular implementation.
[src:rust/ch06-01-defining-an-enum] As such, Rust does not have nulls, but it does have an enum that can encode the concept of a value being present or absent.
[src:rust/ch06-01-defining-an-enum] The `Option<T>` enum is so useful that it’s even included in the prelude; you don’t need to bring it into scope explicitly.
[src:rust/ch06-01-defining-an-enum] Its variants are also included in the prelude: You can use `Some` and `None` directly without the `Option::` prefix.
[src:rust/ch06-01-defining-an-enum] The `Option<T>` enum is still just a regular enum, and `Some(T)` and `None` are still variants of type `Option<T>`.
[src:rust/ch06-01-defining-an-enum] The `<T>` syntax is a feature of Rust we haven’t talked about yet.
[src:rust/ch06-01-defining-an-enum] It’s a generic type parameter, and we’ll cover generics in more detail in Chapter 10.
[src:rust/ch06-01-defining-an-enum] For now, all you need to know is that `<T>` means that the `Some` variant of the `Option` enum can hold one piece of data of any type, and that each concrete type that gets used in place of `T` makes the overall `Option<T>` type a different type.
[src:rust/ch06-01-defining-an-enum] The type of `some_number` is `Option<i32>`.
[src:rust/ch06-01-defining-an-enum] The type of `some_char` is `Option<char>`, which is a different type.
[src:rust/ch06-01-defining-an-enum] Rust can infer these types because we’ve specified a value inside the `Some` variant.
[src:rust/ch06-01-defining-an-enum] For `absent_number`, Rust requires us to annotate the overall `Option` type: The compiler can’t infer the type that the corresponding `Some` variant will hold by looking only at a `None` value.
[src:rust/ch06-01-defining-an-enum] Here, we tell Rust that we mean for `absent_number` to be of type `Option<i32>`.
[src:rust/ch06-01-defining-an-enum] When we have a `Some` value, we know that a value is present, and the value is held within the `Some`.
[src:rust/ch06-01-defining-an-enum] When we have a `None` value, in some sense it means the same thing as null: We don’t have a valid value.
[src:rust/ch06-01-defining-an-enum] So, why is having `Option<T>` any better than having null?
[src:rust/ch06-01-defining-an-enum] In short, because `Option<T>` and `T` (where `T` can be any type) are different types, the compiler won’t let us use an `Option<T>` value as if it were definitely a valid value.
[src:rust/ch06-01-defining-an-enum] In effect, this error message means that Rust doesn’t understand how to add an `i8` and an `Option<i8>`, because they’re different types.
[src:rust/ch06-01-defining-an-enum] When we have a value of a type like `i8` in Rust, the compiler will ensure that we always have a valid value.
[src:rust/ch06-01-defining-an-enum] We can proceed confidently without having to check for null before using that value.
[src:rust/ch06-01-defining-an-enum] Only when we have an `Option<i8>` (or whatever type of value we’re working with) do we have to worry about possibly not having a value, and the compiler will make sure we handle that case before using the value.
[src:rust/ch06-01-defining-an-enum] In other words, you have to convert an `Option<T>` to a `T` before you can perform `T` operations with it.
[src:rust/ch06-01-defining-an-enum] Generally, this helps catch one of the most common issues with null: assuming that something isn’t null when it actually is.
[src:rust/ch06-01-defining-an-enum] Eliminating the risk of incorrectly assuming a not-null value helps you be more confident in your code.
[src:rust/ch06-01-defining-an-enum] In order to have a value that can possibly be null, you must explicitly opt in by making the type of that value `Option<T>`.
[src:rust/ch06-01-defining-an-enum] Then, when you use that value, you are required to explicitly handle the case when the value is null.
[src:rust/ch06-01-defining-an-enum] Everywhere that a value has a type that isn’t an `Option<T>`, you *can* safely assume that the value isn’t null.
[src:rust/ch06-01-defining-an-enum] This was a deliberate design decision for Rust to limit null’s pervasiveness and increase the safety of Rust code.
[src:rust/ch06-01-defining-an-enum] So how do you get the `T` value out of a `Some` variant when you have a value of type `Option<T>` so that you can use that value?
[src:rust/ch06-01-defining-an-enum] The `Option<T>` enum has a large number of methods that are useful in a variety of situations; you can check them out in its documentation.
[src:rust/ch06-01-defining-an-enum] Becoming familiar with the methods on `Option<T>` will be extremely useful in your journey with Rust.
[src:rust/ch06-01-defining-an-enum] In general, in order to use an `Option<T>` value, you want to have code that will handle each variant.
[src:rust/ch06-01-defining-an-enum] You want some code that will run only when you have a `Some(T)` value, and this code is allowed to use the inner `T`.
[src:rust/ch06-01-defining-an-enum] You want some other code to run only if you have a `None` value, and that code doesn’t have a `T` value available.
[src:rust/ch06-01-defining-an-enum] The `match` expression is a control flow construct that does just this when used with enums: It will run different code depending on which variant of the enum it has, and that code can use the data inside the matching value.
[src:rust/ch08-01-vectors] The first collection type we’ll look at is `Vec<T>`, also known as a vector.
[src:rust/ch08-01-vectors] Vectors allow you to store more than one value in a single data structure that puts all the values next to each other in memory.
[src:rust/ch08-01-vectors] Vectors can only store values of the same type.
[src:rust/ch08-01-vectors] They are useful when you have a list of items, such as the lines of text in a file or the prices of items in a shopping cart.
[src:rust/ch08-01-vectors] To create a new, empty vector, we call the `Vec::new` function, as shown in Listing 8-1.
[src:rust/ch08-01-vectors] Note that we added a type annotation here.
[src:rust/ch08-01-vectors] Because we aren’t inserting any values into this vector, Rust doesn’t know what kind of elements we intend to store.
[src:rust/ch08-01-vectors] Vectors are implemented using generics; we’ll cover how to use generics with your own types in Chapter 10.
[src:rust/ch08-01-vectors] For now, know that the `Vec<T>` type provided by the standard library can hold any type.
[src:rust/ch08-01-vectors] When we create a vector to hold a specific type, we can specify the type within angle brackets.
[src:rust/ch08-01-vectors] In Listing 8-1, we’ve told Rust that the `Vec<T>` in `v` will hold elements of the `i32` type.
[src:rust/ch08-01-vectors] More often, you’ll create a `Vec<T>` with initial values, and Rust will infer the type of value you want to store, so you rarely need to do this type annotation.
[src:rust/ch08-01-vectors] Rust conveniently provides the `vec!` macro, which will create a new vector that holds the values you give it.
[src:rust/ch08-01-vectors] Listing 8-2 creates a new `Vec<i32>` that holds the values `1`, `2`, and `3`.
[src:rust/ch08-01-vectors] The integer type is `i32` because that’s the default integer type, as we discussed in the “Data Types” section of Chapter 3.
[src:rust/ch08-01-vectors] Because we’ve given initial `i32` values, Rust can infer that the type of `v` is `Vec<i32>`, and the type annotation isn’t necessary.
[src:rust/ch08-01-vectors] Next, we’ll look at how to modify a vector.
[src:rust/ch08-01-vectors] To create a vector and then add elements to it, we can use the `push` method, as shown in Listing 8-3.
[src:rust/ch08-01-vectors] As with any variable, if we want to be able to change its value, we need to make it mutable using the `mut` keyword, as discussed in Chapter 3.
[src:rust/ch08-01-vectors] The numbers we place inside are all of type `i32`, and Rust infers this from the data, so we don’t need the `Vec<i32>` annotation.
[src:rust/ch08-01-vectors] There are two ways to reference a value stored in a vector: via indexing or by using the `get` method.
[src:rust/ch08-01-vectors] In the following examples, we’ve annotated the types of the values that are returned from these functions for extra clarity.
[src:rust/ch08-01-vectors] Listing 8-4 shows both methods of accessing a value in a vector, with indexing syntax and the `get` method.
[src:rust/ch08-01-vectors] We use the index value of `2` to get the third element because vectors are indexed by number, starting at zero.
[src:rust/ch08-01-vectors] Using `&` and `[]` gives us a reference to the element at the index value.
[src:rust/ch08-01-vectors] When we use the `get` method with the index passed as an argument, we get an `Option<&T>` that we can use with `match`.
[src:rust/ch08-01-vectors] Rust provides these two ways to reference an element so that you can choose how the program behaves when you try to use an index value outside the range of existing elements.
[src:rust/ch08-01-vectors] As an example, let’s see what happens when we have a vector of five elements and then we try to access an element at index 100 with each technique, as shown in Listing 8-5.
[src:rust/ch08-01-vectors] When we run this code, the first `[]` method will cause the program to panic because it references a nonexistent element.
[src:rust/ch08-01-vectors] This method is best used when you want your program to crash if there’s an attempt to access an element past the end of the vector.
[src:rust/ch08-01-vectors] When the `get` method is passed an index that is outside the vector, it returns `None` without panicking.
[src:rust/ch08-01-vectors] You would use this method if accessing an element beyond the range of the vector may happen occasionally under normal circumstances.
[src:rust/ch08-01-vectors] Your code will then have logic to handle having either `Some(&element)` or `None`, as discussed in Chapter 6.
[src:rust/ch08-01-vectors] For example, the index could be coming from a person entering a number.
[src:rust/ch08-01-vectors] If they accidentally enter a number that’s too large and the program gets a `None` value, you could tell the user how many items are in the current vector and give them another chance to enter a valid value.
[src:rust/ch08-01-vectors] That would be more user-friendly than crashing the program due to a typo!
[src:rust/ch08-01-vectors] When the program has a valid reference, the borrow checker enforces the ownership and borrowing rules (covered in Chapter 4) to ensure that this reference and any other references to the contents of the vector remain valid.
[src:rust/ch08-01-vectors] Recall the rule that states you can’t have mutable and immutable references in the same scope.
[src:rust/ch08-01-vectors] That rule applies in Listing 8-6, where we hold an immutable reference to the first element in a vector and try to add an element to the end.
[src:rust/ch08-01-vectors] This program won’t work if we also try to refer to that element later in the function.
[src:rust/ch08-01-vectors] The code in Listing 8-6 might look like it should work: Why should a reference to the first element care about changes at the end of the vector?
[src:rust/ch08-01-vectors] In that case, the reference to the first element would be pointing to deallocated memory.
[src:rust/ch08-01-vectors] The borrowing rules prevent programs from ending up in that situation.
[src:rust/ch08-01-vectors] Note: For more on the implementation details of the `Vec<T>` type, see “The Rustonomicon”.
[src:rust/ch08-01-vectors] To access each element in a vector in turn, we would iterate through all of the elements rather than use indices to access one at a time.
[src:rust/ch08-01-vectors] Listing 8-7 shows how to use a `for` loop to get immutable references to each element in a vector of `i32` values and print them.
[src:rust/ch08-01-vectors] We can also iterate over mutable references to each element in a mutable vector in order to make changes to all the elements.
[src:rust/ch08-01-vectors] The `for` loop in Listing 8-8 will add `50` to each element.
[src:rust/ch08-01-vectors] To change the value that the mutable reference refers to, we have to use the `*` dereference operator to get to the value in `i` before we can use the `+=` operator.
[src:rust/ch08-01-vectors] We’ll talk more about the dereference operator in the “Following the Reference to the Value” section of Chapter 15.
[src:rust/ch08-01-vectors] Iterating over a vector, whether immutably or mutably, is safe because of the borrow checker’s rules.
[src:rust/ch08-01-vectors] If we attempted to insert or remove items in the `for` loop bodies in Listing 8-7 and Listing 8-8, we would get a compiler error similar to the one we got with the code in Listing 8-6.
[src:rust/ch08-01-vectors] The reference to the vector that the `for` loop holds prevents simultaneous modification of the whole vector.
[src:rust/ch08-01-vectors] Vectors can only store values that are of the same type.
[src:rust/ch08-01-vectors] This can be inconvenient; there are definitely use cases for needing to store a list of items of different types.
[src:rust/ch08-01-vectors] Fortunately, the variants of an enum are defined under the same enum type, so when we need one type to represent elements of different types, we can define and use an enum!
[src:rust/ch08-01-vectors] For example, say we want to get values from a row in a spreadsheet in which some of the columns in the row contain integers, some floating-point numbers, and some strings.
[src:rust/ch08-01-vectors] We can define an enum whose variants will hold the different value types, and all the enum variants will be considered the same type: that of the enum.
[src:rust/ch08-01-vectors] Then, we can create a vector to hold that enum and so, ultimately, hold different types.
[src:rust/ch08-01-vectors] Rust needs to know what types will be in the vector at compile time so that it knows exactly how much memory on the heap will be needed to store each element.
[src:rust/ch08-01-vectors] We must also be explicit about what types are allowed in this vector.
[src:rust/ch08-01-vectors] If Rust allowed a vector to hold any type, there would be a chance that one or more of the types would cause errors with the operations performed on the elements of the vector.
[src:rust/ch08-01-vectors] Using an enum plus a `match` expression means that Rust will ensure at compile time that every possible case is handled, as discussed in Chapter 6.
[src:rust/ch08-01-vectors] If you don’t know the exhaustive set of types a program will get at runtime to store in a vector, the enum technique won’t work.
[src:rust/ch08-01-vectors] Instead, you can use a trait object, which we’ll cover in Chapter 18.
[src:rust/ch08-01-vectors] Now that we’ve discussed some of the most common ways to use vectors, be sure to review the API documentation for all of the many useful methods defined on `Vec<T>` by the standard library.
[src:rust/ch08-01-vectors] For example, in addition to `push`, a `pop` method removes and returns the last element.
[src:rust/ch08-01-vectors] Like any other `struct`, a vector is freed when it goes out of scope, as annotated in Listing 8-10.
[src:rust/ch08-01-vectors] When the vector gets dropped, all of its contents are also dropped, meaning the integers it holds will be cleaned up.
[src:rust/ch08-01-vectors] The borrow checker ensures that any references to contents of a vector are only used while the vector itself is valid.
[src:rust/ch08-01-vectors] Let’s move on to the next collection type: `String`!
[src:rust/ch08-02-strings] We talked about strings in Chapter 4, but we’ll look at them in more depth now.
[src:rust/ch08-02-strings] New Rustaceans commonly get stuck on strings for a combination of three reasons: Rust’s propensity for exposing possible errors, strings being a more complicated data structure than many programmers give them credit for, and UTF-8.
[src:rust/ch08-02-strings] These factors combine in a way that can seem difficult when you’re coming from other programming languages.
[src:rust/ch08-02-strings] We discuss strings in the context of collections because strings are implemented as a collection of bytes, plus some methods to provide useful functionality when those bytes are interpreted as text.
[src:rust/ch08-02-strings] In this section, we’ll talk about the operations on `String` that every collection type has, such as creating, updating, and reading.
[src:rust/ch08-02-strings] We’ll also discuss the ways in which `String` is different from the other collections, namely, how indexing into a `String` is complicated by the differences between how people and computers interpret `String` data.
[src:rust/ch08-02-strings] We’ll first define what we mean by the term *string*.
[src:rust/ch08-02-strings] Rust has only one string type in the core language, which is the string slice `str` that is usually seen in its borrowed form, `&str`.
[src:rust/ch08-02-strings] In Chapter 4, we talked about string slices, which are references to some UTF-8 encoded string data stored elsewhere.
[src:rust/ch08-02-strings] String literals, for example, are stored in the program’s binary and are therefore string slices.
[src:rust/ch08-02-strings] The `String` type, which is provided by Rust’s standard library rather than coded into the core language, is a growable, mutable, owned, UTF-8 encoded string type.
[src:rust/ch08-02-strings] When Rustaceans refer to “strings” in Rust, they might be referring to either the `String` or the string slice `&str` types, not just one of those types.
[src:rust/ch08-02-strings] Although this section is largely about `String`, both types are used heavily in Rust’s standard library, and both `String` and string slices are UTF-8 encoded.
[src:rust/ch08-02-strings] Many of the same operations available with `Vec<T>` are available with `String` as well because `String` is actually implemented as a wrapper around a vector of bytes with some extra guarantees, restrictions, and capabilities.
[src:rust/ch08-02-strings] An example of a function that works the same way with `Vec<T>` and `String` is the `new` function to create an instance, shown in Listing 8-11.
[src:rust/ch08-02-strings] This line creates a new, empty string called `s`, into which we can then load data.
[src:rust/ch08-02-strings] Often, we’ll have some initial data with which we want to start the string.
[src:rust/ch08-02-strings] For that, we use the `to_string` method, which is available on any type that implements the `Display` trait, as string literals do.
[src:rust/ch08-02-strings] This code creates a string containing `initial contents`.
[src:rust/ch08-02-strings] We can also use the function `String::from` to create a `String` from a string literal.
[src:rust/ch08-02-strings] The code in Listing 8-13 is equivalent to the code in Listing 8-12 that uses `to_string`.
[src:rust/ch08-02-strings] Because strings are used for so many things, we can use many different generic APIs for strings, providing us with a lot of options.
[src:rust/ch08-02-strings] Some of them can seem redundant, but they all have their place!
[src:rust/ch08-02-strings] In this case, `String::from` and `to_string` do the same thing, so which one you choose is a matter of style and readability.
[src:rust/ch08-02-strings] Remember that strings are UTF-8 encoded, so we can include any properly encoded data in them, as shown in Listing 8-14.
[src:rust/ch08-02-strings] A `String` can grow in size and its contents can change, just like the contents of a `Vec<T>`, if you push more data into it.
[src:rust/ch08-02-strings] In addition, you can conveniently use the `+` operator or the `format!` macro to concatenate `String` values.
[src:rust/ch08-02-strings] We can grow a `String` by using the `push_str` method to append a string slice, as shown in Listing 8-15.
[src:rust/ch08-02-strings] After these two lines, `s` will contain `foobar`.
[src:rust/ch08-02-strings] The `push_str` method takes a string slice because we don’t necessarily want to take ownership of the parameter.
[src:rust/ch08-02-strings] For example, in the code in Listing 8-16, we want to be able to use `s2` after appending its contents to `s1`.
[src:rust/ch08-02-strings] If the `push_str` method took ownership of `s2`, we wouldn’t be able to print its value on the last line.
[src:rust/ch08-02-strings] However, this code works as we’d expect!
[src:rust/ch08-02-strings] The `push` method takes a single character as a parameter and adds it to the `String`.
[src:rust/ch08-02-strings] Listing 8-17 adds the letter *l* to a `String` using the `push` method.
[src:rust/ch08-02-strings] Often, you’ll want to combine two existing strings.
[src:rust/ch08-02-strings] One way to do so is to use the `+` operator, as shown in Listing 8-18.
[src:rust/ch08-02-strings] The string `s3` will contain `Hello, world!`.
[src:rust/ch08-02-strings] The reason `s1` is no longer valid after the addition, and the reason we used a reference to `s2`, has to do with the signature of the method that’s called when we use the `+` operator.
[src:rust/ch08-02-strings] In the standard library, you’ll see `add` defined using generics and associated types.
[src:rust/ch08-02-strings] Here, we’ve substituted in concrete types, which is what happens when we call this method with `String` values.
[src:rust/ch08-02-strings] This signature gives us the clues we need in order to understand the tricky bits of the `+` operator.
[src:rust/ch08-02-strings] First, `s2` has an `&`, meaning that we’re adding a reference of the second string to the first string.
[src:rust/ch08-02-strings] This is because of the `s` parameter in the `add` function: We can only add a string slice to a `String`; we can’t add two `String` values together.
[src:rust/ch08-02-strings] But wait—the type of `&s2` is `&String`, not `&str`, as specified in the second parameter to `add`.
[src:rust/ch08-02-strings] The reason we’re able to use `&s2` in the call to `add` is that the compiler can coerce the `&String` argument into a `&str`.
[src:rust/ch08-02-strings] When we call the `add` method, Rust uses a deref coercion, which here turns `&s2` into `&s2[..]`.
[src:rust/ch08-02-strings] We’ll discuss deref coercion in more depth in Chapter 15.
[src:rust/ch08-02-strings] Because `add` does not take ownership of the `s` parameter, `s2` will still be a valid `String` after this operation.
[src:rust/ch08-02-strings] Second, we can see in the signature that `add` takes ownership of `self` because `self` does *not* have an `&`.
[src:rust/ch08-02-strings] This means `s1` in Listing 8-18 will be moved into the `add` call and will no longer be valid after that.
[src:rust/ch08-02-strings] So, although `let s3 = s1 + &s2;` looks like it will copy both strings and create a new one, this statement actually takes ownership of `s1`, appends a copy of the contents of `s2`, and then returns ownership of the result.
[src:rust/ch08-02-strings] In other words, it looks like it’s making a lot of copies, but it isn’t; the implementation is more efficient than copying.
[src:rust/ch08-02-strings] At this point, `s` will be `tic-tac-toe`.
[src:rust/ch08-02-strings] With all of the `+` and `"` characters, it’s difficult to see what’s going on.
[src:rust/ch08-02-strings] This code also sets `s` to `tic-tac-toe`.
[src:rust/ch08-02-strings] The `format!` macro works like `println!`, but instead of printing the output to the screen, it returns a `String` with the contents.
[src:rust/ch08-02-strings] The version of the code using `format!` is much easier to read, and the code generated by the `format!` macro uses references so that this call doesn’t take ownership of any of its parameters.
[src:rust/ch08-02-strings] In many other programming languages, accessing individual characters in a string by referencing them by index is a valid and common operation.
[src:rust/ch08-02-strings] However, if you try to access parts of a `String` using indexing syntax in Rust, you’ll get an error.
[src:rust/ch08-02-strings] Consider the invalid code in Listing 8-19.
[src:rust/ch08-02-strings] The error tells the story: Rust strings don’t support indexing.
[src:rust/ch08-02-strings] To answer that question, we need to discuss how Rust stores strings in memory.
[src:rust/ch08-02-strings] A `String` is a wrapper over a `Vec<u8>`.
[src:rust/ch08-02-strings] Let’s look at some of our properly encoded UTF-8 example strings from Listing 8-14.
[src:rust/ch08-02-strings] In this case, `len` will be `4`, which means the vector storing the string `"Hola"` is 4 bytes long.
[src:rust/ch08-02-strings] Each of these letters takes 1 byte when encoded in UTF-8.
[src:rust/ch08-02-strings] If you were asked how long the string is, you might say 12.
[src:rust/ch08-02-strings] In fact, Rust’s answer is 24: That’s the number of bytes it takes to encode “Здравствуйте” in UTF-8, because each Unicode scalar value in that string takes 2 bytes of storage.
[src:rust/ch08-02-strings] Therefore, an index into the string’s bytes will not always correlate to a valid Unicode scalar value.
[src:rust/ch08-02-strings] You already know that `answer` will not be `З`, the first letter.
[src:rust/ch08-02-strings] When encoded in UTF-8, the first byte of `З` is `208` and the second is `151`, so it would seem that `answer` should in fact be `208`, but `208` is not a valid character on its own.
[src:rust/ch08-02-strings] Returning `208` is likely not what a user would want if they asked for the first letter of this string; however, that’s the only data that Rust has at byte index 0.
[src:rust/ch08-02-strings] Users generally don’t want the byte value returned, even if the string contains only Latin letters: If `&"hi"[0]` were valid code that returned the byte value, it would return `104`, not `h`.
[src:rust/ch08-02-strings] The answer, then, is that to avoid returning an unexpected value and causing bugs that might not be discovered immediately, Rust doesn’t compile this code at all and prevents misunderstandings early in the development process.
[src:rust/ch08-02-strings] Another point about UTF-8 is that there are actually three relevant ways to look at strings from Rust’s perspective: as bytes, scalar values, and grapheme clusters (the closest thing to what we would call *letters*).
[src:rust/ch08-02-strings] That’s 18 bytes and is how computers ultimately store this data.
[src:rust/ch08-02-strings] There are six `char` values here, but the fourth and sixth are not letters: They’re diacritics that don’t make sense on their own.
[src:rust/ch08-02-strings] Rust provides different ways of interpreting the raw string data that computers store so that each program can choose the interpretation it needs, no matter what human language the data is in.
[src:rust/ch08-02-strings] A final reason Rust doesn’t allow us to index into a `String` to get a character is that indexing operations are expected to always take constant time (O(1)).
[src:rust/ch08-02-strings] But it isn’t possible to guarantee that performance with a `String`, because Rust would have to walk through the contents from the beginning to the index to determine how many valid characters there were.
[src:rust/ch08-02-strings] Indexing into a string is often a bad idea because it’s not clear what the return type of the string-indexing operation should be: a byte value, a character, a grapheme cluster, or a string slice.
[src:rust/ch08-02-strings] If you really need to use indices to create string slices, therefore, Rust asks you to be more specific.
[src:rust/ch08-02-strings] Here, `s` will be a `&str` that contains the first 4 bytes of the string.
[src:rust/ch08-02-strings] Earlier, we mentioned that each of these characters was 2 bytes, which means `s` will be `Зд`.
[src:rust/ch08-02-strings] You should use caution when creating string slices with ranges, because doing so can crash your program.
[src:rust/ch08-02-strings] The best way to operate on pieces of strings is to be explicit about whether you want characters or bytes.
[src:rust/ch08-02-strings] For individual Unicode scalar values, use the `chars` method.
[src:rust/ch08-02-strings] But be sure to remember that valid Unicode scalar values may be made up of more than 1 byte.
[src:rust/ch08-02-strings] Getting grapheme clusters from strings, as with the Devanagari script, is complex, so this functionality is not provided by the standard library.
[src:rust/ch08-02-strings] Crates are available on crates.io if this is the functionality you need.
[src:rust/ch08-02-strings] Different programming languages make different choices about how to present this complexity to the programmer.
[src:rust/ch08-02-strings] Rust has chosen to make the correct handling of `String` data the default behavior for all Rust programs, which means programmers have to put more thought into handling UTF-8 data up front.
[src:rust/ch08-02-strings] This trade-off exposes more of the complexity of strings than is apparent in other programming languages, but it prevents you from having to handle errors involving non-ASCII characters later in your development life cycle.
[src:rust/ch08-02-strings] The good news is that the standard library offers a lot of functionality built off the `String` and `&str` types to help handle these complex situations correctly.
[src:rust/ch08-02-strings] Be sure to check out the documentation for useful methods like `contains` for searching in a string and `replace` for substituting parts of a string with another string.
[src:rust/ch08-02-strings] Let’s switch to something a bit less complex: hash maps!
[src:rust/ch08-03-hash-maps] The last of our common collections is the hash map.
[src:rust/ch08-03-hash-maps] The type `HashMap<K, V>` stores a mapping of keys of type `K` to values of type `V` using a *hashing function*, which determines how it places these keys and values into memory.
[src:rust/ch08-03-hash-maps] Many programming languages support this kind of data structure, but they often use a different name, such as *hash*, *map*, *object*, *hash table*, *dictionary*, or *associative array*, just to name a few.
[src:rust/ch08-03-hash-maps] Hash maps are useful when you want to look up data not by using an index, as you can with vectors, but by using a key that can be of any type.
[src:rust/ch08-03-hash-maps] For example, in a game, you could keep track of each team’s score in a hash map in which each key is a team’s name and the values are each team’s score.
[src:rust/ch08-03-hash-maps] Given a team name, you can retrieve its score.
[src:rust/ch08-03-hash-maps] We’ll go over the basic API of hash maps in this section, but many more goodies are hiding in the functions defined on `HashMap<K, V>` by the standard library.
[src:rust/ch08-03-hash-maps] As always, check the standard library documentation for more information.
[src:rust/ch08-03-hash-maps] One way to create an empty hash map is to use `new` and to add elements with `insert`.
[src:rust/ch08-03-hash-maps] In Listing 8-20, we’re keeping track of the scores of two teams whose names are *Blue* and *Yellow*.
[src:rust/ch08-03-hash-maps] The Blue team starts with 10 points, and the Yellow team starts with 50.
[src:rust/ch08-03-hash-maps] Note that we need to first `use` the `HashMap` from the collections portion of the standard library.
[src:rust/ch08-03-hash-maps] Of our three common collections, this one is the least often used, so it’s not included in the features brought into scope automatically in the prelude.
[src:rust/ch08-03-hash-maps] Hash maps also have less support from the standard library; there’s no built-in macro to construct them, for example.
[src:rust/ch08-03-hash-maps] Just like vectors, hash maps store their data on the heap.
[src:rust/ch08-03-hash-maps] This `HashMap` has keys of type `String` and values of type `i32`.
[src:rust/ch08-03-hash-maps] Like vectors, hash maps are homogeneous: All of the keys must have the same type, and all of the values must have the same type.
[src:rust/ch08-03-hash-maps] We can get a value out of the hash map by providing its key to the `get` method, as shown in Listing 8-21.
[src:rust/ch08-03-hash-maps] Here, `score` will have the value that’s associated with the Blue team, and the result will be `10`.
[src:rust/ch08-03-hash-maps] The `get` method returns an `Option<&V>`; if there’s no value for that key in the hash map, `get` will return `None`.
[src:rust/ch08-03-hash-maps] This program handles the `Option` by calling `copied` to get an `Option<i32>` rather than an `Option<&i32>`, then `unwrap_or` to set `score` to zero if `scores` doesn’t have an entry for the key.
[src:rust/ch08-03-hash-maps] For types that implement the `Copy` trait, like `i32`, the values are copied into the hash map.
[src:rust/ch08-03-hash-maps] For owned values like `String`, the values will be moved and the hash map will be the owner of those values, as demonstrated in Listing 8-22.
[src:rust/ch08-03-hash-maps] We aren’t able to use the variables `field_name` and `field_value` after they’ve been moved into the hash map with the call to `insert`.
[src:rust/ch08-03-hash-maps] If we insert references to values into the hash map, the values won’t be moved into the hash map.
[src:rust/ch08-03-hash-maps] The values that the references point to must be valid for at least as long as the hash map is valid.
[src:rust/ch08-03-hash-maps] We’ll talk more about these issues in “Validating References with Lifetimes” in Chapter 10.
[src:rust/ch08-03-hash-maps] Although the number of key and value pairs is growable, each unique key can only have one value associated with it at a time (but not vice versa: For example, both the Blue team and the Yellow team could have the value `10` stored in the `scores` hash map).
[src:rust/ch08-03-hash-maps] When you want to change the data in a hash map, you have to decide how to handle the case when a key already has a value assigned.
[src:rust/ch08-03-hash-maps] You could replace the old value with the new value, completely disregarding the old value.
[src:rust/ch08-03-hash-maps] You could keep the old value and ignore the new value, only adding the new value if the key *doesn’t* already have a value.
[src:rust/ch08-03-hash-maps] Or you could combine the old value and the new value.
[src:rust/ch08-03-hash-maps] If we insert a key and a value into a hash map and then insert that same key with a different value, the value associated with that key will be replaced.
[src:rust/ch08-03-hash-maps] Even though the code in Listing 8-23 calls `insert` twice, the hash map will only contain one key-value pair because we’re inserting the value for the Blue team’s key both times.
[src:rust/ch08-03-hash-maps] The original value of `10` has been overwritten.
[src:rust/ch08-03-hash-maps] It’s common to check whether a particular key already exists in the hash map with a value and then to take the following actions: If the key does exist in the hash map, the existing value should remain the way it is; if the key doesn’t exist, insert it and a value for it.
[src:rust/ch08-03-hash-maps] Hash maps have a special API for this called `entry` that takes the key you want to check as a parameter.
[src:rust/ch08-03-hash-maps] The return value of the `entry` method is an enum called `Entry` that represents a value that might or might not exist.
[src:rust/ch08-03-hash-maps] Let’s say we want to check whether the key for the Yellow team has a value associated with it.
[src:rust/ch08-03-hash-maps] If it doesn’t, we want to insert the value `50`, and the same for the Blue team.
[src:rust/ch08-03-hash-maps] Using the `entry` API, the code looks like Listing 8-24.
[src:rust/ch08-03-hash-maps] The `or_insert` method on `Entry` is defined to return a mutable reference to the value for the corresponding `Entry` key if that key exists, and if not, it inserts the parameter as the new value for this key and returns a mutable reference to the new value.
[src:rust/ch08-03-hash-maps] This technique is much cleaner than writing the logic ourselves and, in addition, plays more nicely with the borrow checker.
[src:rust/ch08-03-hash-maps] Running the code in Listing 8-24 will print `{"Yellow": 50, "Blue": 10}`.
[src:rust/ch08-03-hash-maps] The first call to `entry` will insert the key for the Yellow team with the value `50` because the Yellow team doesn’t have a value already.
[src:rust/ch08-03-hash-maps] The second call to `entry` will not change the hash map, because the Blue team already has the value `10`.
[src:rust/ch08-03-hash-maps] Another common use case for hash maps is to look up a key’s value and then update it based on the old value.
[src:rust/ch08-03-hash-maps] For instance, Listing 8-25 shows code that counts how many times each word appears in some text.
[src:rust/ch08-03-hash-maps] We use a hash map with the words as keys and increment the value to keep track of how many times we’ve seen that word.
[src:rust/ch08-03-hash-maps] If it’s the first time we’ve seen a word, we’ll first insert the value `0`.
[src:rust/ch08-03-hash-maps] You might see the same key-value pairs printed in a different order: Recall from “Accessing Values in a Hash Map” that iterating over a hash map happens in an arbitrary order.
[src:rust/ch08-03-hash-maps] The `split_whitespace` method returns an iterator over subslices, separated by whitespace, of the value in `text`.
[src:rust/ch08-03-hash-maps] The `or_insert` method returns a mutable reference (`&mut V`) to the value for the specified key.
[src:rust/ch08-03-hash-maps] Here, we store that mutable reference in the `count` variable, so in order to assign to that value, we must first dereference `count` using the asterisk (`*`).
[src:rust/ch08-03-hash-maps] The mutable reference goes out of scope at the end of the `for` loop, so all of these changes are safe and allowed by the borrowing rules.
[src:rust/ch08-03-hash-maps] By default, `HashMap` uses a hashing function called *SipHash* that can provide resistance to denial-of-service (DoS) attacks involving hash tables.
[src:rust/ch08-03-hash-maps] This is not the fastest hashing algorithm available, but the trade-off for better security that comes with the drop in performance is worth it.
[src:rust/ch08-03-hash-maps] If you profile your code and find that the default hash function is too slow for your purposes, you can switch to another function by specifying a different hasher.
[src:rust/ch08-03-hash-maps] A *hasher* is a type that implements the `BuildHasher` trait.
[src:rust/ch08-03-hash-maps] We’ll talk about traits and how to implement them in Chapter 10.
[src:rust/ch08-03-hash-maps] You don’t necessarily have to implement your own hasher from scratch; crates.io has libraries shared by other Rust users that provide hashers implementing many common hashing algorithms.
[src:rust/ch08-03-hash-maps] Vectors, strings, and hash maps will provide a large amount of functionality necessary in programs when you need to store, access, and modify data.
[src:rust/ch08-03-hash-maps] The first consonant of each word is moved to the end of the word and *ay* is added, so *first* becomes *irst-fay*.
[src:rust/ch08-03-hash-maps] Words that start with a vowel have *hay* added to the end instead (*apple* becomes *apple-hay*).
[src:rust/ch08-03-hash-maps] Keep in mind the details about UTF-8 encoding!
[src:rust/ch08-03-hash-maps] The standard library API documentation describes methods that vectors, strings, and hash maps have that will be helpful for these exercises!
[src:rust/ch08-03-hash-maps] We’re getting into more complex programs in which operations can fail, so it’s a perfect time to discuss error handling.
[src:rust/ch09-02-recoverable-errors-with-result] Most errors aren’t serious enough to require the program to stop entirely.
[src:rust/ch09-02-recoverable-errors-with-result] Sometimes when a function fails, it’s for a reason that you can easily interpret and respond to.
[src:rust/ch09-02-recoverable-errors-with-result] For example, if you try to open a file and that operation fails because the file doesn’t exist, you might want to create the file instead of terminating the process.
[src:rust/ch09-02-recoverable-errors-with-result] The `T` and `E` are generic type parameters: We’ll discuss generics in more detail in Chapter 10.
[src:rust/ch09-02-recoverable-errors-with-result] What you need to know right now is that `T` represents the type of the value that will be returned in a success case within the `Ok` variant, and `E` represents the type of the error that will be returned in a failure case within the `Err` variant.
[src:rust/ch09-02-recoverable-errors-with-result] Because `Result` has these generic type parameters, we can use the `Result` type and the functions defined on it in many different situations where the success value and error value we want to return may differ.
[src:rust/ch09-02-recoverable-errors-with-result] Let’s call a function that returns a `Result` value because the function could fail.
[src:rust/ch09-02-recoverable-errors-with-result] The return type of `File::open` is a `Result<T, E>`.
[src:rust/ch09-02-recoverable-errors-with-result] The generic parameter `T` has been filled in by the implementation of `File::open` with the type of the success value, `std::fs::File`, which is a file handle.
[src:rust/ch09-02-recoverable-errors-with-result] The type of `E` used in the error value is `std::io::Error`.
[src:rust/ch09-02-recoverable-errors-with-result] This return type means the call to `File::open` might succeed and return a file handle that we can read from or write to.
[src:rust/ch09-02-recoverable-errors-with-result] The function call also might fail: For example, the file might not exist, or we might not have permission to access the file.
[src:rust/ch09-02-recoverable-errors-with-result] The `File::open` function needs to have a way to tell us whether it succeeded or failed and at the same time give us either the file handle or error information.
[src:rust/ch09-02-recoverable-errors-with-result] This information is exactly what the `Result` enum conveys.
[src:rust/ch09-02-recoverable-errors-with-result] In the case where `File::open` succeeds, the value in the variable `greeting_file_result` will be an instance of `Ok` that contains a file handle.
[src:rust/ch09-02-recoverable-errors-with-result] In the case where it fails, the value in `greeting_file_result` will be an instance of `Err` that contains more information about the kind of error that occurred.
[src:rust/ch09-02-recoverable-errors-with-result] We need to add to the code in Listing 9-3 to take different actions depending on the value `File::open` returns.
[src:rust/ch09-02-recoverable-errors-with-result] Listing 9-4 shows one way to handle the `Result` using a basic tool, the `match` expression that we discussed in Chapter 6.
[src:rust/ch09-02-recoverable-errors-with-result] Note that, like the `Option` enum, the `Result` enum and its variants have been brought into scope by the prelude, so we don’t need to specify `Result::` before the `Ok` and `Err` variants in the `match` arms.
[src:rust/ch09-02-recoverable-errors-with-result] When the result is `Ok`, this code will return the inner `file` value out of the `Ok` variant, and we then assign that file handle value to the variable `greeting_file`.
[src:rust/ch09-02-recoverable-errors-with-result] After the `match`, we can use the file handle for reading or writing.
[src:rust/ch09-02-recoverable-errors-with-result] The other arm of the `match` handles the case where we get an `Err` value from `File::open`.
[src:rust/ch09-02-recoverable-errors-with-result] In this example, we’ve chosen to call the `panic!` macro.
[src:rust/ch09-02-recoverable-errors-with-result] As usual, this output tells us exactly what has gone wrong.
[src:rust/ch09-02-recoverable-errors-with-result] The code in Listing 9-4 will `panic!` no matter why `File::open` failed.
[src:rust/ch09-02-recoverable-errors-with-result] However, we want to take different actions for different failure reasons.
[src:rust/ch09-02-recoverable-errors-with-result] If `File::open` failed because the file doesn’t exist, we want to create the file and return the handle to the new file.
[src:rust/ch09-02-recoverable-errors-with-result] If `File::open` failed for any other reason—for example, because we didn’t have permission to open the file—we still want the code to `panic!` in the same way it did in Listing 9-4.
[src:rust/ch09-02-recoverable-errors-with-result] For this, we add an inner `match` expression, shown in Listing 9-5.
[src:rust/ch09-02-recoverable-errors-with-result] The type of the value that `File::open` returns inside the `Err` variant is `io::Error`, which is a struct provided by the standard library.
[src:rust/ch09-02-recoverable-errors-with-result] This struct has a method, `kind`, that we can call to get an `io::ErrorKind` value.
[src:rust/ch09-02-recoverable-errors-with-result] The enum `io::ErrorKind` is provided by the standard library and has variants representing the different kinds of errors that might result from an `io` operation.
[src:rust/ch09-02-recoverable-errors-with-result] The variant we want to use is `ErrorKind::NotFound`, which indicates the file we’re trying to open doesn’t exist yet.
[src:rust/ch09-02-recoverable-errors-with-result] So, we match on `greeting_file_result`, but we also have an inner match on `error.kind()`.
[src:rust/ch09-02-recoverable-errors-with-result] The condition we want to check in the inner match is whether the value returned by `error.kind()` is the `NotFound` variant of the `ErrorKind` enum.
[src:rust/ch09-02-recoverable-errors-with-result] If it is, we try to create the file with `File::create`.
[src:rust/ch09-02-recoverable-errors-with-result] However, because `File::create` could also fail, we need a second arm in the inner `match` expression.
[src:rust/ch09-02-recoverable-errors-with-result] When the file can’t be created, a different error message is printed.
[src:rust/ch09-02-recoverable-errors-with-result] The second arm of the outer `match` stays the same, so the program panics on any error besides the missing file error.
[src:rust/ch09-02-recoverable-errors-with-result] The `match` expression is very useful but also very much a primitive.
[src:rust/ch09-02-recoverable-errors-with-result] In Chapter 13, you’ll learn about closures, which are used with many of the methods defined on `Result<T, E>`.
[src:rust/ch09-02-recoverable-errors-with-result] These methods can be more concise than using `match` when handling `Result<T, E>` values in your code.
[src:rust/ch09-02-recoverable-errors-with-result] Although this code has the same behavior as Listing 9-5, it doesn’t contain any `match` expressions and is cleaner to read.
[src:rust/ch09-02-recoverable-errors-with-result] Come back to this example after you’ve read Chapter 13 and look up the `unwrap_or_else` method in the standard library documentation.
[src:rust/ch09-02-recoverable-errors-with-result] Many more of these methods can clean up huge, nested `match` expressions when you’re dealing with errors.
[src:rust/ch09-02-recoverable-errors-with-result] Using `match` works well enough, but it can be a bit verbose and doesn’t always communicate intent well.
[src:rust/ch09-02-recoverable-errors-with-result] The `Result<T, E>` type has many helper methods defined on it to do various, more specific tasks.
[src:rust/ch09-02-recoverable-errors-with-result] The `unwrap` method is a shortcut method implemented just like the `match` expression we wrote in Listing 9-4.
[src:rust/ch09-02-recoverable-errors-with-result] If the `Result` value is the `Ok` variant, `unwrap` will return the value inside the `Ok`.
[src:rust/ch09-02-recoverable-errors-with-result] If the `Result` is the `Err` variant, `unwrap` will call the `panic!` macro for us.
[src:rust/ch09-02-recoverable-errors-with-result] Similarly, the `expect` method lets us also choose the `panic!` error message.
[src:rust/ch09-02-recoverable-errors-with-result] Using `expect` instead of `unwrap` and providing good error messages can convey your intent and make tracking down the source of a panic easier.
[src:rust/ch09-02-recoverable-errors-with-result] We use `expect` in the same way as `unwrap`: to return the file handle or call the `panic!` macro.
[src:rust/ch09-02-recoverable-errors-with-result] The error message used by `expect` in its call to `panic!` will be the parameter that we pass to `expect`, rather than the default `panic!` message that `unwrap` uses.
[src:rust/ch09-02-recoverable-errors-with-result] In production-quality code, most Rustaceans choose `expect` rather than `unwrap` and give more context about why the operation is expected to always succeed.
[src:rust/ch09-02-recoverable-errors-with-result] That way, if your assumptions are ever proven wrong, you have more information to use in debugging.
[src:rust/ch09-02-recoverable-errors-with-result] When a function’s implementation calls something that might fail, instead of handling the error within the function itself, you can return the error to the calling code so that it can decide what to do.
[src:rust/ch09-02-recoverable-errors-with-result] This is known as *propagating* the error and gives more control to the calling code, where there might be more information or logic that dictates how the error should be handled than what you have available in the context of your code.
[src:rust/ch09-02-recoverable-errors-with-result] For example, Listing 9-6 shows a function that reads a username from a file.
[src:rust/ch09-02-recoverable-errors-with-result] If the file doesn’t exist or can’t be read, this function will return those errors to the code that called the function.
[src:rust/ch09-02-recoverable-errors-with-result] This function can be written in a much shorter way, but we’re going to start by doing a lot of it manually in order to explore error handling; at the end, we’ll show the shorter way.
[src:rust/ch09-02-recoverable-errors-with-result] Let’s look at the return type of the function first: `Result<String, io::Error>`.
[src:rust/ch09-02-recoverable-errors-with-result] This means the function is returning a value of the type `Result<T, E>`, where the generic parameter `T` has been filled in with the concrete type `String` and the generic type `E` has been filled in with the concrete type `io::Error`.
[src:rust/ch09-02-recoverable-errors-with-result] If this function succeeds without any problems, the code that calls this function will receive an `Ok` value that holds a `String`—the `username` that this function read from the file.
[src:rust/ch09-02-recoverable-errors-with-result] If this function encounters any problems, the calling code will receive an `Err` value that holds an instance of `io::Error` that contains more information about what the problems were.
[src:rust/ch09-02-recoverable-errors-with-result] We chose `io::Error` as the return type of this function because that happens to be the type of the error value returned from both of the operations we’re calling in this function’s body that might fail: the `File::open` function and the `read_to_string` method.
[src:rust/ch09-02-recoverable-errors-with-result] The body of the function starts by calling the `File::open` function.
[src:rust/ch09-02-recoverable-errors-with-result] Then, we handle the `Result` value with a `match` similar to the `match` in Listing 9-4.
[src:rust/ch09-02-recoverable-errors-with-result] If `File::open` succeeds, the file handle in the pattern variable `file` becomes the value in the mutable variable `username_file` and the function continues.
[src:rust/ch09-02-recoverable-errors-with-result] In the `Err` case, instead of calling `panic!`, we use the `return` keyword to return early out of the function entirely and pass the error value from `File::open`, now in the pattern variable `e`, back to the calling code as this function’s error value.
[src:rust/ch09-02-recoverable-errors-with-result] So, if we have a file handle in `username_file`, the function then creates a new `String` in variable `username` and calls the `read_to_string` method on the file handle in `username_file` to read the contents of the file into `username`.
[src:rust/ch09-02-recoverable-errors-with-result] The `read_to_string` method also returns a `Result` because it might fail, even though `File::open` succeeded.
[src:rust/ch09-02-recoverable-errors-with-result] So, we need another `match` to handle that `Result`: If `read_to_string` succeeds, then our function has succeeded, and we return the username from the file that’s now in `username` wrapped in an `Ok`.
[src:rust/ch09-02-recoverable-errors-with-result] If `read_to_string` fails, we return the error value in the same way that we returned the error value in the `match` that handled the return value of `File::open`.
[src:rust/ch09-02-recoverable-errors-with-result] However, we don’t need to explicitly say `return`, because this is the last expression in the function.
[src:rust/ch09-02-recoverable-errors-with-result] The code that calls this code will then handle getting either an `Ok` value that contains a username or an `Err` value that contains an `io::Error`.
[src:rust/ch09-02-recoverable-errors-with-result] It’s up to the calling code to decide what to do with those values.
[src:rust/ch09-02-recoverable-errors-with-result] If the calling code gets an `Err` value, it could call `panic!` and crash the program, use a default username, or look up the username from somewhere other than a file, for example.
[src:rust/ch09-02-recoverable-errors-with-result] We don’t have enough information on what the calling code is actually trying to do, so we propagate all the success or error information upward for it to handle appropriately.
[src:rust/ch09-02-recoverable-errors-with-result] This pattern of propagating errors is so common in Rust that Rust provides the question mark operator `?` to make this easier.
[src:rust/ch09-02-recoverable-errors-with-result] Listing 9-7 shows an implementation of `read_username_from_file` that has the same functionality as in Listing 9-6, but this implementation uses the `?` operator.
[src:rust/ch09-02-recoverable-errors-with-result] The `?` placed after a `Result` value is defined to work in almost the same way as the `match` expressions that we defined to handle the `Result` values in Listing 9-6.
[src:rust/ch09-02-recoverable-errors-with-result] If the value of the `Result` is an `Ok`, the value inside the `Ok` will get returned from this expression, and the program will continue.
[src:rust/ch09-02-recoverable-errors-with-result] If the value is an `Err`, the `Err` will be returned from the whole function as if we had used the `return` keyword so that the error value gets propagated to the calling code.
[src:rust/ch09-02-recoverable-errors-with-result] When the `?` operator calls the `from` function, the error type received is converted into the error type defined in the return type of the current function.
[src:rust/ch09-02-recoverable-errors-with-result] This is useful when a function returns one error type to represent all the ways a function might fail, even if parts might fail for many different reasons.
[src:rust/ch09-02-recoverable-errors-with-result] For example, we could change the `read_username_from_file` function in Listing 9-7 to return a custom error type named `OurError` that we define.
[src:rust/ch09-02-recoverable-errors-with-result] If we also define `impl From<io::Error> for OurError` to construct an instance of `OurError` from an `io::Error`, then the `?` operator calls in the body of `read_username_from_file` will call `from` and convert the error types without needing to add any more code to the function.
[src:rust/ch09-02-recoverable-errors-with-result] In the context of Listing 9-7, the `?` at the end of the `File::open` call will return the value inside an `Ok` to the variable `username_file`.
[src:rust/ch09-02-recoverable-errors-with-result] If an error occurs, the `?` operator will return early out of the whole function and give any `Err` value to the calling code.
[src:rust/ch09-02-recoverable-errors-with-result] The same thing applies to the `?` at the end of the `read_to_string` call.
[src:rust/ch09-02-recoverable-errors-with-result] The `?` operator eliminates a lot of boilerplate and makes this function’s implementation simpler.
[src:rust/ch09-02-recoverable-errors-with-result] We could even shorten this code further by chaining method calls immediately after the `?`, as shown in Listing 9-8.
[src:rust/ch09-02-recoverable-errors-with-result] We’ve moved the creation of the new `String` in `username` to the beginning of the function; that part hasn’t changed.
[src:rust/ch09-02-recoverable-errors-with-result] Instead of creating a variable `username_file`, we’ve chained the call to `read_to_string` directly onto the result of `File::open("hello.txt")?`.
[src:rust/ch09-02-recoverable-errors-with-result] We still have a `?` at the end of the `read_to_string` call, and we still return an `Ok` value containing `username` when both `File::open` and `read_to_string` succeed rather than returning errors.
[src:rust/ch09-02-recoverable-errors-with-result] The functionality is again the same as in Listing 9-6 and Listing 9-7; this is just a different, more ergonomic way to write it.
[src:rust/ch09-02-recoverable-errors-with-result] Listing 9-9 shows a way to make this even shorter using `fs::read_to_string`.
[src:rust/ch09-02-recoverable-errors-with-result] Reading a file into a string is a fairly common operation, so the standard library provides the convenient `fs::read_to_string` function that opens the file, creates a new `String`, reads the contents of the file, puts the contents into that `String`, and returns it.
[src:rust/ch09-02-recoverable-errors-with-result] Of course, using `fs::read_to_string` doesn’t give us the opportunity to explain all the error handling, so we did it the longer way first.
[src:rust/ch09-02-recoverable-errors-with-result] The `?` operator can only be used in functions whose return type is compatible with the value the `?` is used on.
[src:rust/ch09-02-recoverable-errors-with-result] This is because the `?` operator is defined to perform an early return of a value out of the function, in the same manner as the `match` expression we defined in Listing 9-6.
[src:rust/ch09-02-recoverable-errors-with-result] In Listing 9-6, the `match` was using a `Result` value, and the early return arm returned an `Err(e)` value.
[src:rust/ch09-02-recoverable-errors-with-result] The return type of the function has to be a `Result` so that it’s compatible with this `return`.
[src:rust/ch09-02-recoverable-errors-with-result] In Listing 9-10, let’s look at the error we’ll get if we use the `?` operator in a `main` function with a return type that is incompatible with the type of the value we use `?` on.
[src:rust/ch09-02-recoverable-errors-with-result] This code opens a file, which might fail.
[src:rust/ch09-02-recoverable-errors-with-result] The `?` operator follows the `Result` value returned by `File::open`, but this `main` function has the return type of `()`, not `Result`.
[src:rust/ch09-02-recoverable-errors-with-result] This error points out that we’re only allowed to use the `?` operator in a function that returns `Result`, `Option`, or another type that implements `FromResidual`.
[src:rust/ch09-02-recoverable-errors-with-result] One choice is to change the return type of your function to be compatible with the value you’re using the `?` operator on as long as you have no restrictions preventing that.
[src:rust/ch09-02-recoverable-errors-with-result] The other choice is to use a `match` or one of the `Result<T, E>` methods to handle the `Result<T, E>` in whatever way is appropriate.
[src:rust/ch09-02-recoverable-errors-with-result] The error message also mentioned that `?` can be used with `Option<T>` values as well.
[src:rust/ch09-02-recoverable-errors-with-result] As with using `?` on `Result`, you can only use `?` on `Option` in a function that returns an `Option`.
[src:rust/ch09-02-recoverable-errors-with-result] The behavior of the `?` operator when called on an `Option<T>` is similar to its behavior when called on a `Result<T, E>`: If the value is `None`, the `None` will be returned early from the function at that point.
[src:rust/ch09-02-recoverable-errors-with-result] If the value is `Some`, the value inside the `Some` is the resultant value of the expression, and the function continues.
[src:rust/ch09-02-recoverable-errors-with-result] Listing 9-11 has an example of a function that finds the last character of the first line in the given text.
[src:rust/ch09-02-recoverable-errors-with-result] This function returns `Option<char>` because it’s possible that there is a character there, but it’s also possible that there isn’t.
[src:rust/ch09-02-recoverable-errors-with-result] This code takes the `text` string slice argument and calls the `lines` method on it, which returns an iterator over the lines in the string.
[src:rust/ch09-02-recoverable-errors-with-result] Because this function wants to examine the first line, it calls `next` on the iterator to get the first value from the iterator.
[src:rust/ch09-02-recoverable-errors-with-result] If `text` is the empty string, this call to `next` will return `None`, in which case we use `?` to stop and return `None` from `last_char_of_first_line`.
[src:rust/ch09-02-recoverable-errors-with-result] If `text` is not the empty string, `next` will return a `Some` value containing a string slice of the first line in `text`.
[src:rust/ch09-02-recoverable-errors-with-result] The `?` extracts the string slice, and we can call `chars` on that string slice to get an iterator of its characters.
[src:rust/ch09-02-recoverable-errors-with-result] We’re interested in the last character in this first line, so we call `last` to return the last item in the iterator.
[src:rust/ch09-02-recoverable-errors-with-result] This is an `Option` because it’s possible that the first line is the empty string; for example, if `text` starts with a blank line but has characters on other lines, as in `"\nhi"`.
[src:rust/ch09-02-recoverable-errors-with-result] However, if there is a last character on the first line, it will be returned in the `Some` variant.
[src:rust/ch09-02-recoverable-errors-with-result] The `?` operator in the middle gives us a concise way to express this logic, allowing us to implement the function in one line.
[src:rust/ch09-02-recoverable-errors-with-result] If we couldn’t use the `?` operator on `Option`, we’d have to implement this logic using more method calls or a `match` expression.
[src:rust/ch09-02-recoverable-errors-with-result] Note that you can use the `?` operator on a `Result` in a function that returns `Result`, and you can use the `?` operator on an `Option` in a function that returns `Option`, but you can’t mix and match.
[src:rust/ch09-02-recoverable-errors-with-result] The `?` operator won’t automatically convert a `Result` to an `Option` or vice versa; in those cases, you can use methods like the `ok` method on `Result` or the `ok_or` method on `Option` to do the conversion explicitly.
[src:rust/ch09-02-recoverable-errors-with-result] So far, all the `main` functions we’ve used return `()`.
[src:rust/ch09-02-recoverable-errors-with-result] The `main` function is special because it’s the entry point and exit point of an executable program, and there are restrictions on what its return type can be for the program to behave as expected.
[src:rust/ch09-02-recoverable-errors-with-result] Luckily, `main` can also return a `Result<(), E>`.
[src:rust/ch09-02-recoverable-errors-with-result] Listing 9-12 has the code from Listing 9-10, but we’ve changed the return type of `main` to be `Result<(), Box<dyn Error>>` and added a return value `Ok(())` to the end.
[src:rust/ch09-02-recoverable-errors-with-result] The `Box<dyn Error>` type is a trait object, which we’ll talk about in “Using Trait Objects to Abstract over Shared Behavior” in Chapter 18.
[src:rust/ch09-02-recoverable-errors-with-result] For now, you can read `Box<dyn Error>` to mean “any kind of error.” Using `?` on a `Result` value in a `main` function with the error type `Box<dyn Error>` is allowed because it allows any `Err` value to be returned early.
[src:rust/ch09-02-recoverable-errors-with-result] Even though the body of this `main` function will only ever return errors of type `std::io::Error`, by specifying `Box<dyn Error>`, this signature will continue to be correct even if more code that returns other errors is added to the body of `main`.
[src:rust/ch09-02-recoverable-errors-with-result] When a `main` function returns a `Result<(), E>`, the executable will exit with a value of `0` if `main` returns `Ok(())` and will exit with a nonzero value if `main` returns an `Err` value.
[src:rust/ch09-02-recoverable-errors-with-result] Executables written in C return integers when they exit: Programs that exit successfully return the integer `0`, and programs that error return some integer other than `0`.
[src:rust/ch09-02-recoverable-errors-with-result] Rust also returns integers from executables to be compatible with this convention.
[src:rust/ch09-02-recoverable-errors-with-result] The `main` function may return any types that implement the `std::process::Termination` trait, which contains a function `report` that returns an `ExitCode`.
[src:rust/ch09-02-recoverable-errors-with-result] Consult the standard library documentation for more information on implementing the `Termination` trait for your own types.
[src:rust/ch09-02-recoverable-errors-with-result] Now that we’ve discussed the details of calling `panic!` or returning `Result`, let’s return to the topic of how to decide which is appropriate to use in which cases.
[src:rust/ch10-02-traits] A *trait* defines the functionality a particular type has and can share with other types.
[src:rust/ch10-02-traits] We can use traits to define shared behavior in an abstract way.
[src:rust/ch10-02-traits] We can use *trait bounds* to specify that a generic type can be any type that has certain behavior.
[src:rust/ch10-02-traits] Note: Traits are similar to a feature often called *interfaces* in other languages, although with some differences.
[src:rust/ch10-02-traits] A type’s behavior consists of the methods we can call on that type.
[src:rust/ch10-02-traits] Different types share the same behavior if we can call the same methods on all of those types.
[src:rust/ch10-02-traits] Trait definitions are a way to group method signatures together to define a set of behaviors necessary to accomplish some purpose.
[src:rust/ch10-02-traits] We want to make a media aggregator library crate named `aggregator` that can display summaries of data that might be stored in a `NewsArticle` or `SocialPost` instance.
[src:rust/ch10-02-traits] To do this, we need a summary from each type, and we’ll request that summary by calling a `summarize` method on an instance.
[src:rust/ch10-02-traits] Listing 10-12 shows the definition of a public `Summary` trait that expresses this behavior.
[src:rust/ch10-02-traits] Here, we declare a trait using the `trait` keyword and then the trait’s name, which is `Summary` in this case.
[src:rust/ch10-02-traits] We also declare the trait as `pub` so that crates depending on this crate can make use of this trait too, as we’ll see in a few examples.
[src:rust/ch10-02-traits] Inside the curly brackets, we declare the method signatures that describe the behaviors of the types that implement this trait, which in this case is `fn summarize(&self) -> String`.
[src:rust/ch10-02-traits] After the method signature, instead of providing an implementation within curly brackets, we use a semicolon.
[src:rust/ch10-02-traits] Each type implementing this trait must provide its own custom behavior for the body of the method.
[src:rust/ch10-02-traits] The compiler will enforce that any type that has the `Summary` trait will have the method `summarize` defined with this signature exactly.
[src:rust/ch10-02-traits] A trait can have multiple methods in its body: The method signatures are listed one per line, and each line ends in a semicolon.
[src:rust/ch10-02-traits] Now that we’ve defined the desired signatures of the `Summary` trait’s methods, we can implement it on the types in our media aggregator.
[src:rust/ch10-02-traits] Listing 10-13 shows an implementation of the `Summary` trait on the `NewsArticle` struct that uses the headline, the author, and the location to create the return value of `summarize`.
[src:rust/ch10-02-traits] For the `SocialPost` struct, we define `summarize` as the username followed by the entire text of the post, assuming that the post content is already limited to 280 characters.
[src:rust/ch10-02-traits] Implementing a trait on a type is similar to implementing regular methods.
[src:rust/ch10-02-traits] The difference is that after `impl`, we put the trait name we want to implement, then use the `for` keyword, and then specify the name of the type we want to implement the trait for.
[src:rust/ch10-02-traits] Within the `impl` block, we put the method signatures that the trait definition has defined.
[src:rust/ch10-02-traits] Instead of adding a semicolon after each signature, we use curly brackets and fill in the method body with the specific behavior that we want the methods of the trait to have for the particular type.
[src:rust/ch10-02-traits] Now that the library has implemented the `Summary` trait on `NewsArticle` and `SocialPost`, users of the crate can call the trait methods on instances of `NewsArticle` and `SocialPost` in the same way we call regular methods.
[src:rust/ch10-02-traits] The only difference is that the user must bring the trait into scope as well as the types.
[src:rust/ch10-02-traits] This code prints `1 new post: horse_ebooks: of course, as you probably already know, people`.
[src:rust/ch10-02-traits] Other crates that depend on the `aggregator` crate can also bring the `Summary` trait into scope to implement `Summary` on their own types.
[src:rust/ch10-02-traits] One restriction to note is that we can implement a trait on a type only if either the trait or the type, or both, are local to our crate.
[src:rust/ch10-02-traits] For example, we can implement standard library traits like `Display` on a custom type like `SocialPost` as part of our `aggregator` crate functionality because the type `SocialPost` is local to our `aggregator` crate.
[src:rust/ch10-02-traits] We can also implement `Summary` on `Vec<T>` in our `aggregator` crate because the trait `Summary` is local to our `aggregator` crate.
[src:rust/ch10-02-traits] But we can’t implement external traits on external types.
[src:rust/ch10-02-traits] For example, we can’t implement the `Display` trait on `Vec<T>` within our `aggregator` crate, because `Display` and `Vec<T>` are both defined in the standard library and aren’t local to our `aggregator` crate.
[src:rust/ch10-02-traits] This restriction is part of a property called *coherence*, and more specifically the *orphan rule*, so named because the parent type is not present.
[src:rust/ch10-02-traits] This rule ensures that other people’s code can’t break your code and vice versa.
[src:rust/ch10-02-traits] Without the rule, two crates could implement the same trait for the same type, and Rust wouldn’t know which implementation to use.
[src:rust/ch10-02-traits] Sometimes it’s useful to have default behavior for some or all of the methods in a trait instead of requiring implementations for all methods on every type.
[src:rust/ch10-02-traits] Then, as we implement the trait on a particular type, we can keep or override each method’s default behavior.
[src:rust/ch10-02-traits] In Listing 10-14, we specify a default string for the `summarize` method of the `Summary` trait instead of only defining the method signature, as we did in Listing 10-12.
[src:rust/ch10-02-traits] To use a default implementation to summarize instances of `NewsArticle`, we specify an empty `impl` block with `impl Summary for NewsArticle {}`.
[src:rust/ch10-02-traits] Even though we’re no longer defining the `summarize` method on `NewsArticle` directly, we’ve provided a default implementation and specified that `NewsArticle` implements the `Summary` trait.
[src:rust/ch10-02-traits] This code prints `New article available!
[src:rust/ch10-02-traits] Creating a default implementation doesn’t require us to change anything about the implementation of `Summary` on `SocialPost` in Listing 10-13.
[src:rust/ch10-02-traits] The reason is that the syntax for overriding a default implementation is the same as the syntax for implementing a trait method that doesn’t have a default implementation.
[src:rust/ch10-02-traits] Default implementations can call other methods in the same trait, even if those other methods don’t have a default implementation.
[src:rust/ch10-02-traits] In this way, a trait can provide a lot of useful functionality and only require implementors to specify a small part of it.
[src:rust/ch10-02-traits] After we define `summarize_author`, we can call `summarize` on instances of the `SocialPost` struct, and the default implementation of `summarize` will call the definition of `summarize_author` that we’ve provided.
[src:rust/ch10-02-traits] Because we’ve implemented `summarize_author`, the `Summary` trait has given us the behavior of the `summarize` method without requiring us to write any more code.
[src:rust/ch10-02-traits] This code prints `1 new post: (Read more from @horse_ebooks...)`.
[src:rust/ch10-02-traits] Note that it isn’t possible to call the default implementation from an overriding implementation of that same method.
[src:rust/ch10-02-traits] Now that you know how to define and implement traits, we can explore how to use traits to define functions that accept many different types.
[src:rust/ch10-02-traits] We’ll use the `Summary` trait we implemented on the `NewsArticle` and `SocialPost` types in Listing 10-13 to define a `notify` function that calls the `summarize` method on its `item` parameter, which is of some type that implements the `Summary` trait.
[src:rust/ch10-02-traits] Instead of a concrete type for the `item` parameter, we specify the `impl` keyword and the trait name.
[src:rust/ch10-02-traits] This parameter accepts any type that implements the specified trait.
[src:rust/ch10-02-traits] In the body of `notify`, we can call any methods on `item` that come from the `Summary` trait, such as `summarize`.
[src:rust/ch10-02-traits] We can call `notify` and pass in any instance of `NewsArticle` or `SocialPost`.
[src:rust/ch10-02-traits] Code that calls the function with any other type, such as a `String` or an `i32`, won’t compile, because those types don’t implement `Summary`.
[src:rust/ch10-02-traits] This longer form is equivalent to the example in the previous section but is more verbose.
[src:rust/ch10-02-traits] We place trait bounds with the declaration of the generic type parameter after a colon and inside angle brackets.
[src:rust/ch10-02-traits] The `impl Trait` syntax is convenient and makes for more concise code in simple cases, while the fuller trait bound syntax can express more complexity in other cases.
[src:rust/ch10-02-traits] For example, we can have two parameters that implement `Summary`.
[src:rust/ch10-02-traits] Using `impl Trait` is appropriate if we want this function to allow `item1` and `item2` to have different types (as long as both types implement `Summary`).
[src:rust/ch10-02-traits] The generic type `T` specified as the type of the `item1` and `item2` parameters constrains the function such that the concrete type of the value passed as an argument for `item1` and `item2` must be the same.
[src:rust/ch10-02-traits] We can also specify more than one trait bound.
[src:rust/ch10-02-traits] Say we wanted `notify` to use display formatting as well as `summarize` on `item`: We specify in the `notify` definition that `item` must implement both `Display` and `Summary`.
[src:rust/ch10-02-traits] With the two trait bounds specified, the body of `notify` can call `summarize` and use `{}` to format `item`.
[src:rust/ch10-02-traits] Using too many trait bounds has its downsides.
[src:rust/ch10-02-traits] Each generic has its own trait bounds, so functions with multiple generic type parameters can contain lots of trait bound information between the function’s name and its parameter list, making the function signature hard to read.
[src:rust/ch10-02-traits] For this reason, Rust has alternate syntax for specifying trait bounds inside a `where` clause after the function signature.
[src:rust/ch10-02-traits] This function’s signature is less cluttered: The function name, parameter list, and return type are close together, similar to a function without lots of trait bounds.
[src:rust/ch10-02-traits] By using `impl Summary` for the return type, we specify that the `returns_summarizable` function returns some type that implements the `Summary` trait without naming the concrete type.
[src:rust/ch10-02-traits] In this case, `returns_summarizable` returns a `SocialPost`, but the code calling this function doesn’t need to know that.
[src:rust/ch10-02-traits] The ability to specify a return type only by the trait it implements is especially useful in the context of closures and iterators, which we cover in Chapter 13.
[src:rust/ch10-02-traits] Closures and iterators create types that only the compiler knows or types that are very long to specify.
[src:rust/ch10-02-traits] The `impl Trait` syntax lets you concisely specify that a function returns some type that implements the `Iterator` trait without needing to write out a very long type.
[src:rust/ch10-02-traits] However, you can only use `impl Trait` if you’re returning a single type.
[src:rust/ch10-02-traits] Returning either a `NewsArticle` or a `SocialPost` isn’t allowed due to restrictions around how the `impl Trait` syntax is implemented in the compiler.
[src:rust/ch10-02-traits] We’ll cover how to write a function with this behavior in the “Using Trait Objects to Abstract over Shared Behavior” section of Chapter 18.
[src:rust/ch10-02-traits] By using a trait bound with an `impl` block that uses generic type parameters, we can implement methods conditionally for types that implement the specified traits.
[src:rust/ch10-02-traits] For example, the type `Pair<T>` in Listing 10-15 always implements the `new` function to return a new instance of `Pair<T>` (recall from the “Method Syntax” section of Chapter 5 that `Self` is a type alias for the type of the `impl` block, which in this case is `Pair<T>`).
[src:rust/ch10-02-traits] But in the next `impl` block, `Pair<T>` only implements the `cmp_display` method if its inner type `T` implements the `PartialOrd` trait that enables comparison *and* the `Display` trait that enables printing.
[src:rust/ch10-02-traits] We can also conditionally implement a trait for any type that implements another trait.
[src:rust/ch10-02-traits] Implementations of a trait on any type that satisfies the trait bounds are called *blanket implementations* and are used extensively in the Rust standard library.
[src:rust/ch10-02-traits] For example, the standard library implements the `ToString` trait on any type that implements the `Display` trait.
[src:rust/ch10-02-traits] Because the standard library has this blanket implementation, we can call the `to_string` method defined by the `ToString` trait on any type that implements the `Display` trait.
[src:rust/ch10-02-traits] Blanket implementations appear in the documentation for the trait in the “Implementors” section.
[src:rust/ch10-02-traits] Traits and trait bounds let us write code that uses generic type parameters to reduce duplication but also specify to the compiler that we want the generic type to have particular behavior.
[src:rust/ch10-02-traits] The compiler can then use the trait bound information to check that all the concrete types used with our code provide the correct behavior.
[src:rust/ch10-02-traits] In dynamically typed languages, we would get an error at runtime if we called a method on a type that didn’t define the method.
[src:rust/ch10-02-traits] But Rust moves these errors to compile time so that we’re forced to fix the problems before our code is even able to run.
[src:rust/ch10-02-traits] Additionally, we don’t have to write code that checks for behavior at runtime, because we’ve already checked at compile time.
[src:rust/ch10-02-traits] Doing so improves performance without having to give up the flexibility of generics.
[src:rust/ch10-03-lifetime-syntax] Lifetimes are another kind of generic that we’ve already been using.
[src:rust/ch10-03-lifetime-syntax] Rather than ensuring that a type has the behavior we want, lifetimes ensure that references are valid as long as we need them to be.
[src:rust/ch10-03-lifetime-syntax] One detail we didn’t discuss in the “References and Borrowing” section in Chapter 4 is that every reference in Rust has a lifetime, which is the scope for which that reference is valid.
[src:rust/ch10-03-lifetime-syntax] Most of the time, lifetimes are implicit and inferred, just like most of the time, types are inferred.
[src:rust/ch10-03-lifetime-syntax] We are only required to annotate types when multiple types are possible.
[src:rust/ch10-03-lifetime-syntax] In a similar way, we must annotate lifetimes when the lifetimes of references could be related in a few different ways.
[src:rust/ch10-03-lifetime-syntax] Rust requires us to annotate the relationships using generic lifetime parameters to ensure that the actual references used at runtime will definitely be valid.
[src:rust/ch10-03-lifetime-syntax] Annotating lifetimes is not even a concept most other programming languages have, so this is going to feel unfamiliar.
[src:rust/ch10-03-lifetime-syntax] Although we won’t cover lifetimes in their entirety in this chapter, we’ll discuss common ways you might encounter lifetime syntax so that you can get comfortable with the concept.
[src:rust/ch10-03-lifetime-syntax] The main aim of lifetimes is to prevent dangling references, which, if they were allowed to exist, would cause a program to reference data other than the data it’s intended to reference.
[src:rust/ch10-03-lifetime-syntax] Consider the program in Listing 10-16, which has an outer scope and an inner scope.
[src:rust/ch10-03-lifetime-syntax] Note: The examples in Listings 10-16, 10-17, and 10-23 declare variables without giving them an initial value, so the variable name exists in the outer scope.
[src:rust/ch10-03-lifetime-syntax] At first glance, this might appear to be in conflict with Rust having no null values.
[src:rust/ch10-03-lifetime-syntax] However, if we try to use a variable before giving it a value, we’ll get a compile-time error, which shows that indeed Rust does not allow null values.
[src:rust/ch10-03-lifetime-syntax] The outer scope declares a variable named `r` with no initial value, and the inner scope declares a variable named `x` with the initial value of `5`.
[src:rust/ch10-03-lifetime-syntax] Inside the inner scope, we attempt to set the value of `r` as a reference to `x`.
[src:rust/ch10-03-lifetime-syntax] Then, the inner scope ends, and we attempt to print the value in `r`.
[src:rust/ch10-03-lifetime-syntax] This code won’t compile, because the value that `r` is referring to has gone out of scope before we try to use it.
[src:rust/ch10-03-lifetime-syntax] The error message says that the variable `x` “does not live long enough.” The reason is that `x` will be out of scope when the inner scope ends on line 7.
[src:rust/ch10-03-lifetime-syntax] But `r` is still valid for the outer scope; because its scope is larger, we say that it “lives longer.” If Rust allowed this code to work, `r` would be referencing memory that was deallocated when `x` went out of scope, and anything we tried to do with `r` wouldn’t work correctly.
[src:rust/ch10-03-lifetime-syntax] So, how does Rust determine that this code is invalid?
[src:rust/ch10-03-lifetime-syntax] The Rust compiler has a *borrow checker* that compares scopes to determine whether all borrows are valid.
[src:rust/ch10-03-lifetime-syntax] Listing 10-17 shows the same code as Listing 10-16 but with annotations showing the lifetimes of the variables.
[src:rust/ch10-03-lifetime-syntax] Here, we’ve annotated the lifetime of `r` with `'a` and the lifetime of `x` with `'b`.
[src:rust/ch10-03-lifetime-syntax] As you can see, the inner `'b` block is much smaller than the outer `'a` lifetime block.
[src:rust/ch10-03-lifetime-syntax] At compile time, Rust compares the size of the two lifetimes and sees that `r` has a lifetime of `'a` but that it refers to memory with a lifetime of `'b`.
[src:rust/ch10-03-lifetime-syntax] The program is rejected because `'b` is shorter than `'a`: The subject of the reference doesn’t live as long as the reference.
[src:rust/ch10-03-lifetime-syntax] Listing 10-18 fixes the code so that it doesn’t have a dangling reference and it compiles without any errors.
[src:rust/ch10-03-lifetime-syntax] Here, `x` has the lifetime `'b`, which in this case is larger than `'a`.
[src:rust/ch10-03-lifetime-syntax] This means `r` can reference `x` because Rust knows that the reference in `r` will always be valid while `x` is valid.
[src:rust/ch10-03-lifetime-syntax] Now that you know where the lifetimes of references are and how Rust analyzes lifetimes to ensure that references will always be valid, let’s explore generic lifetimes in function parameters and return values.
[src:rust/ch10-03-lifetime-syntax] We’ll write a function that returns the longer of two string slices.
[src:rust/ch10-03-lifetime-syntax] This function will take two string slices and return a single string slice.
[src:rust/ch10-03-lifetime-syntax] After we’ve implemented the `longest` function, the code in Listing 10-19 should print `The longest string is abcd`.
[src:rust/ch10-03-lifetime-syntax] Note that we want the function to take string slices, which are references, rather than strings, because we don’t want the `longest` function to take ownership of its parameters.
[src:rust/ch10-03-lifetime-syntax] Refer to “String Slices as Parameters” in Chapter 4 for more discussion about why the parameters we use in Listing 10-19 are the ones we want.
[src:rust/ch10-03-lifetime-syntax] If we try to implement the `longest` function as shown in Listing 10-20, it won’t compile.
[src:rust/ch10-03-lifetime-syntax] The help text reveals that the return type needs a generic lifetime parameter on it because Rust can’t tell whether the reference being returned refers to `x` or `y`.
[src:rust/ch10-03-lifetime-syntax] Actually, we don’t know either, because the `if` block in the body of this function returns a reference to `x` and the `else` block returns a reference to `y`!
[src:rust/ch10-03-lifetime-syntax] When we’re defining this function, we don’t know the concrete values that will be passed into this function, so we don’t know whether the `if` case or the `else` case will execute.
[src:rust/ch10-03-lifetime-syntax] We also don’t know the concrete lifetimes of the references that will be passed in, so we can’t look at the scopes as we did in Listings 10-17 and 10-18 to determine whether the reference we return will always be valid.
[src:rust/ch10-03-lifetime-syntax] The borrow checker can’t determine this either, because it doesn’t know how the lifetimes of `x` and `y` relate to the lifetime of the return value.
[src:rust/ch10-03-lifetime-syntax] To fix this error, we’ll add generic lifetime parameters that define the relationship between the references so that the borrow checker can perform its analysis.
[src:rust/ch10-03-lifetime-syntax] Lifetime annotations don’t change how long any of the references live.
[src:rust/ch10-03-lifetime-syntax] Rather, they describe the relationships of the lifetimes of multiple references to each other without affecting the lifetimes.
[src:rust/ch10-03-lifetime-syntax] Just as functions can accept any type when the signature specifies a generic type parameter, functions can accept references with any lifetime by specifying a generic lifetime parameter.
[src:rust/ch10-03-lifetime-syntax] Lifetime annotations have a slightly unusual syntax: The names of lifetime parameters must start with an apostrophe (`'`) and are usually all lowercase and very short, like generic types.
[src:rust/ch10-03-lifetime-syntax] Most people use the name `'a` for the first lifetime annotation.
[src:rust/ch10-03-lifetime-syntax] We place lifetime parameter annotations after the `&` of a reference, using a space to separate the annotation from the reference’s type.
[src:rust/ch10-03-lifetime-syntax] One lifetime annotation by itself doesn’t have much meaning, because the annotations are meant to tell Rust how generic lifetime parameters of multiple references relate to each other.
[src:rust/ch10-03-lifetime-syntax] Let’s examine how the lifetime annotations relate to each other in the context of the `longest` function.
[src:rust/ch10-03-lifetime-syntax] To use lifetime annotations in function signatures, we need to declare the generic lifetime parameters inside angle brackets between the function name and the parameter list, just as we did with generic type parameters.
[src:rust/ch10-03-lifetime-syntax] We want the signature to express the following constraint: The returned reference will be valid as long as both of the parameters are valid.
[src:rust/ch10-03-lifetime-syntax] This is the relationship between lifetimes of the parameters and the return value.
[src:rust/ch10-03-lifetime-syntax] We’ll name the lifetime `'a` and then add it to each reference, as shown in Listing 10-21.
[src:rust/ch10-03-lifetime-syntax] This code should compile and produce the result we want when we use it with the `main` function in Listing 10-19.
[src:rust/ch10-03-lifetime-syntax] The function signature now tells Rust that for some lifetime `'a`, the function takes two parameters, both of which are string slices that live at least as long as lifetime `'a`.
[src:rust/ch10-03-lifetime-syntax] The function signature also tells Rust that the string slice returned from the function will live at least as long as lifetime `'a`.
[src:rust/ch10-03-lifetime-syntax] In practice, it means that the lifetime of the reference returned by the `longest` function is the same as the smaller of the lifetimes of the values referred to by the function arguments.
[src:rust/ch10-03-lifetime-syntax] These relationships are what we want Rust to use when analyzing this code.
[src:rust/ch10-03-lifetime-syntax] Remember, when we specify the lifetime parameters in this function signature, we’re not changing the lifetimes of any values passed in or returned.
[src:rust/ch10-03-lifetime-syntax] Rather, we’re specifying that the borrow checker should reject any values that don’t adhere to these constraints.
[src:rust/ch10-03-lifetime-syntax] Note that the `longest` function doesn’t need to know exactly how long `x` and `y` will live, only that some scope can be substituted for `'a` that will satisfy this signature.
[src:rust/ch10-03-lifetime-syntax] When annotating lifetimes in functions, the annotations go in the function signature, not in the function body.
[src:rust/ch10-03-lifetime-syntax] The lifetime annotations become part of the contract of the function, much like the types in the signature.
[src:rust/ch10-03-lifetime-syntax] Having function signatures contain the lifetime contract means the analysis the Rust compiler does can be simpler.
[src:rust/ch10-03-lifetime-syntax] If there’s a problem with the way a function is annotated or the way it is called, the compiler errors can point to the part of our code and the constraints more precisely.
[src:rust/ch10-03-lifetime-syntax] If, instead, the Rust compiler made more inferences about what we intended the relationships of the lifetimes to be, the compiler might only be able to point to a use of our code many steps away from the cause of the problem.
[src:rust/ch10-03-lifetime-syntax] When we pass concrete references to `longest`, the concrete lifetime that is substituted for `'a` is the part of the scope of `x` that overlaps with the scope of `y`.
[src:rust/ch10-03-lifetime-syntax] In other words, the generic lifetime `'a` will get the concrete lifetime that is equal to the smaller of the lifetimes of `x` and `y`.
[src:rust/ch10-03-lifetime-syntax] Because we’ve annotated the returned reference with the same lifetime parameter `'a`, the returned reference will also be valid for the length of the smaller of the lifetimes of `x` and `y`.
[src:rust/ch10-03-lifetime-syntax] Let’s look at how the lifetime annotations restrict the `longest` function by passing in references that have different concrete lifetimes.
[src:rust/ch10-03-lifetime-syntax] Listing 10-22 is a straightforward example.
[src:rust/ch10-03-lifetime-syntax] In this example, `string1` is valid until the end of the outer scope, `string2` is valid until the end of the inner scope, and `result` references something that is valid until the end of the inner scope.
[src:rust/ch10-03-lifetime-syntax] Run this code and you’ll see that the borrow checker approves; it will compile and print `The longest string is long string is long`.
[src:rust/ch10-03-lifetime-syntax] Next, let’s try an example that shows that the lifetime of the reference in `result` must be the smaller lifetime of the two arguments.
[src:rust/ch10-03-lifetime-syntax] We’ll move the declaration of the `result` variable outside the inner scope but leave the assignment of the value to the `result` variable inside the scope with `string2`.
[src:rust/ch10-03-lifetime-syntax] Then, we’ll move the `println!` that uses `result` to outside the inner scope, after the inner scope has ended.
[src:rust/ch10-03-lifetime-syntax] The code in Listing 10-23 will not compile.
[src:rust/ch10-03-lifetime-syntax] The error shows that for `result` to be valid for the `println!` statement, `string2` would need to be valid until the end of the outer scope.
[src:rust/ch10-03-lifetime-syntax] Rust knows this because we annotated the lifetimes of the function parameters and return values using the same lifetime parameter `'a`.
[src:rust/ch10-03-lifetime-syntax] As humans, we can look at this code and see that `string1` is longer than `string2`, and therefore, `result` will contain a reference to `string1`.
[src:rust/ch10-03-lifetime-syntax] Because `string1` has not gone out of scope yet, a reference to `string1` will still be valid for the `println!` statement.
[src:rust/ch10-03-lifetime-syntax] However, the compiler can’t see that the reference is valid in this case.
[src:rust/ch10-03-lifetime-syntax] We’ve told Rust that the lifetime of the reference returned by the `longest` function is the same as the smaller of the lifetimes of the references passed in.
[src:rust/ch10-03-lifetime-syntax] Therefore, the borrow checker disallows the code in Listing 10-23 as possibly having an invalid reference.
[src:rust/ch10-03-lifetime-syntax] Try designing more experiments that vary the values and lifetimes of the references passed in to the `longest` function and how the returned reference is used.
[src:rust/ch10-03-lifetime-syntax] Make hypotheses about whether or not your experiments will pass the borrow checker before you compile; then, check to see if you’re right!
[src:rust/ch10-03-lifetime-syntax] The way in which you need to specify lifetime parameters depends on what your function is doing.
[src:rust/ch10-03-lifetime-syntax] For example, if we changed the implementation of the `longest` function to always return the first parameter rather than the longest string slice, we wouldn’t need to specify a lifetime on the `y` parameter.
[src:rust/ch10-03-lifetime-syntax] We’ve specified a lifetime parameter `'a` for the parameter `x` and the return type, but not for the parameter `y`, because the lifetime of `y` does not have any relationship with the lifetime of `x` or the return value.
